<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 3, Rockies 0  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Off to one of the best starts of his career,
Randy Johnson threw his second shutout and third complete game in
four starts as the Arizona Diamondbacks beat the Colorado Rockies
3-0 on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (4-0) allowed four hits, struck out eight, walked three
and even drove in a run with a single in the sixth inning. The
Diamondbacks' other two runs came on a passed ball by catcher Ben
Petrick and a wild pitch by Brian Bohanon.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is just one out short of having a complete game in all
four starts. In 35 2-3 innings this season, he has struck out 42,
walked five and allowed three earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old left-hander pitched to 102 batters without a
walk before Larry Walker drew a base on balls with one out in the
fourth inning. Johnson had 39 strikeouts during that 29-inning
span.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado starter Rolando Arrojo (1-2) left the game in the
second inning with runners on first and second and no outs. He
strained his left hamstring in the first inning, then bruised his
left calf when he was hit by Travis Lee's line drive to lead off
the second. He left after he couldn't come up with Damian Miller's
soft grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's control finally faltered in the eighth, when he gave
up a single to Neifi Perez, then walked pinch-hitter Jeff Manto and
Brian Hunter to load the bases with two outs. Then, on a 3-2 pitch
with the crowd chanting ''Randy, Randy,'' Johnson caught Lansing
looking for a strikeout to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, which won three out of four from the Rockies, scored an
unearned run off Arrojo in the first when Jay Bell and Luis
Gonzalez walked with one out. They advanced on Erubiel Durazo's
ground out, then Bell scored on a passed ball.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon, who lost his job in the rotation after three horrible
starts, didn't allow a run until he walked Steve Finley and Lee to
start the sixth. The runners moved up on Miller's fly out to right,
then Andy Fox was walked intentionally to load the bases for
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon's wild pitch to Johnson allowed Finley to score, then
Johnson singled up the middle. Lee scored, but Fox was thrown out
at the plate by the center fielder Hunter.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Diamondbacks will activate closer Matt Mantei on
Friday. He's been on the disabled list since April 2 with biceps
tendinitis. ... Walker asked to be in the lineup because he's never
started in three opportunities against Johnson and was livid over a
Denver columnist's suggestion that he was afraid to face the big
lefty. Walker was 0-for-3 with the walk. ... Until Todd Helton's
one-out double in the second, left-handed batters were 0-for-13
against Johnson this season. ... For the second time in two starts,
Johnson had a three-pitch inning, this time in the fifth. He said
he's never had one before in his career.
</P>
</TEXT>
