<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Ruling Hurts Ousted Leader  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- The High Court ruled Friday that
Malaysia's prime minister is not required to testify in the sex
trial of an ousted deputy premier, deflating defense hopes of
proving the charges are politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is not an iota of evidence to show that Dr. Mahathir
Mohamad is involved in a political conspiracy to fabricate evidence
of sodomy to topple Anwar Ibrahim,'' Judge Ariffin Jaka said.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar jumped up, shook his fist at the judge and then pounded it
on the wooden guard rail. ''Where is justice in this court?'' he
shouted. ''You should not allow him to hide behind his executive
privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge's decision ended six months of legal wrangling over a
defense subpoena for the prime minister to answer questions
regarding an alleged political conspiracy to frame Anwar.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar was fired by Mahathir in September 1998, arrested and
charged with corruption. A High Court judge convicted him in April
last year and sentenced him to six years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-deputy prime minister is now on trial on charges of
sodomy, a crime in predominantly Muslim Malaysia, and faces another
20 years imprisonment if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar has maintained throughout that Mahathir and other
government leaders framed him in both cases to quash his chances of
becoming prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Mahathir's presence in court was not relevant
to Anwar's trial on the charge of sodomizing his former driver
Azizan Abu Bakar.
</P>
<P>
   Chief prosecutor Abdul Gani Patail told the court this week that
it was merely a stunt by Anwar's lawyers to ridicule the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   With the issue of Mahathir's testimony resolved, the trial could
now end soon because the defense team has few witnesses left to
call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
