<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Filipinos Celebrate Good Friday  </HEADLINE>
By GLADYS NEBAB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO CUTUD, Philippines (AP) -- Thousands of tourists
flocked here Friday to watch a bizarre highlight of Easter week
celebrations in Asia's largest Catholic nation -- the nailing of
penitents to crosses in a re-enactment of Jesus' death.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine Filipinos, including a woman, were expected to be
''crucified'' on three crosses on a small hill outside San Pedro
Cutud, a farming village north of Manila.
</P>
<P>
   Most stay on the crosses under a hot sun for only a few minutes
in the ritual that has continued for more than 40 years. The
faithful believe it is a form of penance that helps prayers get
answered.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Philippines, thousands of bloody penitents,
including children, observed Good Friday by walking barefoot
through dusty village streets beating their bare backs with ropes
and pieces of wood, splashing spectators with blood.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that the ritual is sufficiently bloody, attendants use
pieces of broken glass to periodically open new cuts on the
penitents' backs.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church officially frowns on the rituals, but does
not attempt to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Filipinos traditionally observe Lent with fasting and acts of
repentance. In Manila, many battled traffic and crowded sanctuaries
late Thursday night in a quest to visit 14 churches representing
the 14 stations of the cross.
</P>
<P>
   In Zamboanga in the southern Philippines, however, churches were
less crowded than usual because of fears of possible bomb attacks.
Scores of people have been killed by recent explosions blamed on
Muslim rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Police and soldiers guarded many churches and streets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
