<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Cops Sentenced in Alcohol Killing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Six former Mexico City policemen convicted of
robbing and killing an American student have been sentenced to
between 68 and 99 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick McPhail, 27, of New York City, was found in his parked
car in Mexico City in November 1998. He had died of alcohol
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   The police officers formed a group that has been accused of
regularly committing crimes against unsuspecting motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the uniformed officers stopped drivers, then
allowed their civilian accomplices to rob them of their money and
credit cards. The assailants then forced the victims to drink a
bottle of alcohol so that they would get drunk and be unable to
identify the attackers, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Leon Gonzalez was sentenced to 85 years in prison on
Wednesday and Lucio Tapia Galindo to 99 years, the Mexico attorney
general's office said. The two were active police officers at the
time of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Their four accomplices had retired from the force when McPhail
died. Three received sentences of 79 years, while a fourth received
68 years, the attorney general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants were sentenced after being convicted of murder,
robbery, kidnapping, and organized crime. The judge gave the
defendants the long sentences to ensure they are not released on
probation. However, under the Federal District's penal code, a
person can't serve more than 50 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   McPhail was living in Mexico and studying at the Ibero-American
University, the attorney general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the suspects were arrested and extradited from Texas
last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
