<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bristol-Myers May Be Merger Target  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With the future of its promising blood-pressure
drug now uncertain, Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. may find itself an
acquisition target or a merger player, some analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers' hopes of launching the next pill destined for
multibillion dollar annual sales were scuttled when federal
officials raised concerns that the experimental hypertension drug
Vanlev may cause severe facial swelling and impair breathing in
some patients.
</P>
<P>
   Those worries led the nation's third-largest drugmaker Wednesday
to withdraw its application for Vanlev until more studies can be
completed, a move that should delay launch of the pill until at
least late next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''A year delay on a potential blockbuster could cause them to
think more actively about merging,'' said Bob Kirby, an analyst
with Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The company is downplaying the need to merge, despite the
consolidation wave sweeping the pharmaceutical industry. But the
officials aren't ruling it out.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not looking back or standing still,'' Michael Mee,
Bristol-Myers' chief financial officer, said in a conference call
Thursday with analysts. ''We are looking at all of our options with
great intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the company's first-quarter earnings rose a
better-than-expected 15 percent, most analysts' focus was clearly
on the company's pipeline of future products -- and the future of
Vanlev.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe a merger is likely if the company cannot
revive Vanlev, a drug expected to post $2 billion or more in annual
sales when it reaches market.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will probably merge if they are not able to revive
Vanlev,'' said Hemant Shah, an analyst with HKS &AMP; Co. He gives the
drug a 50-50 chance of making it on the market without serious
safety warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Companies routinely stumble in developing new drugs -- nine out
of 10 drugs they test in people never make it to market.
</P>
<P>
   But drug firms' pipelines have grown in importance as Wall
Street pressures the firms to show evidence they can continue to
raise profits at double-digit levels. As a result, the New
York-based Bristol-Myers has not shied away from promoting numerous
studies of Vanlev over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers officials acknowledge they expected to have the
drug approved in June, and had no contingency plan for the delay
caused after the Food and Drug Administration raised concerns.
</P>
<P>
   With a market capitalization of more than $100 billion and a
diverse portfolio of products, including medical devices and the
world's leading infant formula, Bristol-Myers remains confident
about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very fortunate that we are not just a one- or two- or
three-product company,'' Mee said.
</P>
<P>
   Other big drugmakers have overcome similar research setbacks,
Kirby said. Merck &AMP; Co. in 1998 disappointed Wall Street when it
announced it was not moving ahead with a promising antidepressant.
And Schering-Plough Corp. was punished last year after the company
ran into safety problems with its experimental impotence pill.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, Wall Street considered Bristol-Myers one of the
most attractive drugmakers. But the Vanlev problem spotlights a
number of potential shortcomings at the company.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the company's top-selling drug, the
cholesterol-lowering pill Pravachol, have declined, losing market
share to Warner-Lambert Co.'s Lipitor. And the company's top cancer
drug Taxol is expected to lose patent protection in the next year
or two, making it vulnerable to cheaper generics.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a New England Journal of Medicine study raised
concerns about another Bristol-Myers' drug. It said Plavix, a new
blood thinner given to heart patients after angioplasty, in rare
cases may trigger a deadly blood disease.
</P>
<P>
   Plavix, which had $201 million in sales in the first quarter, up
128 percent from a year ago, is Bristol-Myers' fastest selling
drug.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers said the side effect was extremely rare and the
study would not have a big impact on sales.
</P>
<P>
   On a positive note, the company said it was resubmitting its new
colorectal cancer drug for FDA approval. Safety questions has been
raised after the drug was first submitted last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers reported earned $1.22 billion, or 61 cents per
diluted share, on revenue of $5.26 billion, up from $1.07 billion,
or 53 cents per share, on revenue of $4.85 billion last year.
Results beat analysts' forecasts by a penny, according to First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.bms.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
