<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Economy Expected To Recover  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's economic planning chief said Friday that
the economy is expected to achieve a ''considerable'' recovery
later this year, but that government stimulus is still necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economy's wheels have finally left the runway,'' Economic
Planning Agency chief Taiichi Sakaiya told a regular news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the economy continues on this flight path, I expect it will
be in a pretty good condition in the second half of the (fiscal)
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Sakaiya warned, however, that the economy still needs
stimulative government policies to keep it on track for sustainable
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economy slipped back into recession late last year after
a period of fitful growth. But rising industrial productivity and
corporate restructuring drives have raised hope that Japan's
decade-long economic slump may be ending.
</P>
<P>
   Sakaiya said he feels consumer spending, one of weakest areas of
the economy, will revive next year as there are signs that wages
are improving in some areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
