<HEADLINE> Demand May Rise for Type of Canola  </HEADLINE>
By BRIAN WITTE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- Demand could rise for a type of canola
with less fatty acid if the government approves new labeling
requirements, a North Dakota canola group says.
</P>
<P>
   Dow AgroSciences, based in Winnipeg, Manitoba, and Cargill of
Minnetonka, Minn., are the first two companies to work with a
variety of lowfat canola called Low Lin.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of Low Lin is that less trans fatty acids are
created when it is changed from a solid to a liquid, said Barry
Coleman, executive director of the Northern Canola Growers
Association. Some health experts believe trans fatty acid
contributes to heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration is considering regulations that
would require companies to show in labeling how much trans fatty
acid is in a product.
</P>
<P>
   ''As demand for healthy oil alternatives increases, so will the
number of growers raising Low Lin canola and the number of
processors and wholesalers bottling it,'' said Tom Borgen,
president of the growers association.
</P>
<P>
   Canola has the lowest level of saturated fat than any edible
oil. Most Low Lin canola is used in the cooking and frying and in
the snack food industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll see a lot of competing oils working to modify their
fatty acid profile,'' Coleman said. ''And canola is probably out in
front of all the competing oils as far as making progress'' in
reducing fatty acid.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota is the nation's leading producer of canola. The
U.S. Department of Agriculture estimates that a record 1.2 million
acres will be planted this year. The department estimated that 1.5
million acres will be planted nationally.
</P>
<P>
   More North Dakota farmers are starting to try Low Lin, but most
are beginning with a small amount, Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Dow AgroSciences has teamed up with Winnipeg-based James
Richardson International grain company to grow a specific variety
of Low Lin canola. JRI contracts most of its production in Canada,
but the company started contracting acres in North Dakota about two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''As more growers see production results by neighboring farmers
and research centers, I expect the acreage to increase,'' said
David Mack, a JRI representative in North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK (AP) -- The Arkansas state legislature may soon
consider creating a state Department of Agriculture or similar
centralized organization that would help farmers in the state get
the most out of their land.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Jan Judy, a Democrat from Fayetteville, offered the
proposal Thursday in a presentation before the state House and
Senate interim committees on agriculture and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ''My hope is that in the next session, we will be able to create
a Department of Agriculture or similar organization,'' Judy said.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas and Rhode Island are the only two states without a
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Such a department would give farmers a place to receive
information concerning their products and the markets, both
domestic or international, supporters of the proposal said.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Ford grows blueberries and blackberries but says there is no
one to help new farmers get started. Instead, the state has ''a
collection of independent agencies'' that have no efficient way of
communicating, Ford said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
