<DOCNO> APW20000421.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ralph Nader Campaigns in Kentucky  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE BAILEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- A longtime advocate for the ''little guy''
with his focus on the perceived evils of corporate America, Ralph
Nader now has other targets in sight: the Republican and Democratic
parties as he runs for president under the Green Party banner.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people like to take on big guys,'' Nader said with a
smirk as he spoke to several hundred supporters Thursday at the
University of Kentucky's Singleton Center for the Arts. ''I like to
take on big guys. Big guys invigorate me. And they should
invigorate you.''
</P>
<P>
   His message was simple: corporations and their lobbyists have
taken over the political system and it is up to citizens to return
the process to its grass-roots origin.
</P>
<P>
   ''You hear so many people today say, 'I'm not into politics,'''
he said. ''Students, if you don't turn on to politics, politics is
going to turn on you. That's a lesson you may learn the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader, 66, ran for president in 1996, but appeared on less than
one-fourth of state ballots. He did not campaign or raise money and
attracted less than 1 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Nader's goal is to get the party on the ballot
in every state and pull more than 5 percent of the vote, which
would qualify him for millions in federal campaign funds. He
currently polls in single digits, along with Reform Party
presidential candidate Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party currently is on the ballot in 13 states,
including New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   Nader promised to wage ''a campaign in every sense of the
word.''
</P>
<P>
   He is up against a handful of challengers for the Green Party
nomination, including Jello Biafra, former lead singer of the punk
rock band the Dead Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Princeton and Harvard, Nader is a lawyer and
author who has fought to bring progress and reform in the areas of
auto safety, worker rights and environmental preservation. In the
late 1960s, he organized citizen action teams around the country
known as ''Nader's Raiders.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader said his platform will revolve around several issues,
including creating a universal health care system and destroying
corporate America's hold on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''The two party system is crumbling. (Ross) Perot started that
crumble,'' he said. ''They are hollowed out and don't have much
basic grass-roots support. They're basically two parties with a lot
of money fighting against each other with 30-second electric combat
ads on television.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only way we are going to regain control of our political
institution is to help build a progressive political movement that
will break up the concentration of wealth and power -- a plutocracy
that reigns over our democracy,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votenader.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 0129 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Completes Fund Raising  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE CASS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore is wrapping up his fund raising with
about $9 million remaining to carry his Democratic presidential
campaign through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, who spent almost twice as much as Gore to
capture the Republican nomination, has less in the bank but is
still raising cash and expects to continue outspending Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore faces a spending limit because he accepted federal matching
funds. Bush, who didn't take the taxpayer money, can spend whatever
he can raise during the remainder of the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spent $73.4 million to lock up the GOP nomination. He
spent $10.1 million last month, when he stopped a tough challenge
from Arizona Sen. John McCain, according to Bush's campaign finance
report filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent $37.7 million -- including $4.7 million in March -- to
fend off former Sen. Bill Bradley, his Federal Election Commission
report showed.
</P>
<P>
   Because some of that spending was exempt from the legal limit,
Gore can spend $9 million more before bumping the ceiling, said
spokesman Douglas Hattaway. He's already raised almost all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We understand that we'll continue to be outspent, but we'll
use our resources wisely and beat him on the issues,'' Hattaway
said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   As of the end of March, Gore had more money: $8.7 million,
including matching funds due from the government, to Bush's $5.7
million. The figures take into account debt of about $1 million for
each.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan noted that the Texas governor
collected another $1.8 million in the first half of this month, and
plans another fund-raiser in Greensboro, N.C., next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have plenty of resources to continue spreading
the governor's compassionate conservative message,'' McClellan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither candidate should suffer the fate of 1996 Republican
nominee Bob Dole, who was down to $2 million by this time and
watched his campaign sink from public view while he awaited the
nominating convention, which brings each party nominee an infusion
of taxpayer cash.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will keep raising cash for the Democratic Party even though
he's appeared at his last presidential campaign fund-raiser -- a
$100,000-plus event last weekend at the home of computer company
executive Jesse Singh in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not holding any more events. We will be doing some fund
raising through direct mail and via the Web site,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway said Gore expects to qualify for a record $15 million
in federal matching funds for the primary season, surpassing 1996
Republican nominee Bob Dole, who received about $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers match the first $250 of each individual contribution.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Bush added another 15 names to his list of 156
''Pioneers'' -- fund-raisers who have brought in $100,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway said Gore, who last year released a list of 25
top-level fund-raisers, doesn't plan to give out any more names.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's big donors included millionaire developer George Argyros
of Costa Mesa, Calif., former owner of the Seattle Mariners;
Gregory Slayton, chairman of the Palo Alto, Calif., tech company My
Software; and Jim Haslam, a Knoxville, Tenn., founder of a chain of
convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Huizenga, founder of National Heritage Academies, one of
the nation's largest chains of for-profit charter schools, and Mark
Guzzetta, a fund-raiser for Bush's brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush,
were also on the list.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Gore raised $1.9 million and Bush raised $5.9 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 0130 </TRAILER>
