<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Premier Seeks Forgiveness  </HEADLINE>
By VESELIN TOSHKOV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) -- Prime Minister Ivan Kostov is admitting
his government made mistakes in the fight against corruption and is
asking the public to forgive him.
</P>
<P>
   Kostov is beset by allegations made by his former interior
minister, Bogomil Bonev, that he covered up intelligence reports
citing specific senior officials as corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   The charges have unleashed a political storm in Bulgaria, where
many people are growing impatient with waiting for improvements in
the economy to trickle down to the ordinary citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Kostov is expected to appear before parliament today to discuss
the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   With average salaries around $110 a month, a growing number of
Bulgarians suspect a few politically well-connected people are the
only ones to have profited from the improvement in the economy
since Kostov took office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide television address Thursday, Kostov admitted he
and his government had made mistakes but said that he will continue
to fulfill his duties.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know that I have made mistake, but I know that (the people)
will forgive me,'' Kostov said. ''I will not drop my
responsibilities as prime minister.''
</P>
<P>
   He also denied allegations of a possible split in the ranks of
his pro-Western Union of Democratic Forces, which could cause a
government crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier public comments, President Petar Stoyanov had urged
Kostov to be ''as honest as possible'' to Bulgarians angry about
the reported corruption.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, one day after Bonev made his allegations, Kostov's
spokesman, Mihail Mihailov, stepped down after a trade union leader
accused him of accepting a bribe to grant a broadcast license.
</P>
<P>
   Mihailov denied the charge but said he was giving up his post to
devote full time to clearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   Stoyanov said that both the UDF leadership and the government
made numerous mistakes, which worsened after the October 1999 local
elections ''due to a lack of courage and resolve on the part of
Prime Minister Kostov, among other things.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What now Bogomil Bonev says, many Bulgarians accept because he
is saying the things Kostov should have said six months ago,''
Stoyanov said.
</P>
<P>
   The main opposition Socialist Party said Wednesday it will push
for a no-confidence vote in parliament against the government.
</P>
<P>
   Although it holds 137 of the 240 seats in the body, the UDF may
be divided over the corruption accusations, meaning some of its
members may vote against the government and with the Socialists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 0204 </TRAILER>
