<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Today  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressSCOREBOARD:
Thursday, April 20:
<TEXT>
<P>
   No games scheduled until playoffs begin Saturday.
STARTING UP:
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs begin Saturday at 12:30 p.m. EDT with Game 1 of the
Detroit-Miami series.
SPREAD OUT:
</P>
<P>
   In a change designed to improve the NBA's cable television
ratings, the first-round matchups are spread over two weeks, with
loads of downtime between games. For example: Game 1 of the
Kings-Lakers series is on Sunday, and the teams don't play again
until Thursday. The Seattle-Seattle Utah series has a four-day
break between Game 2 on Monday and Game 3 on Saturday, then a
three-day break before Game 4 the following Wednesday. The
elongated schedule is part of Turner Sports' new television
contract. Rather than having four games per night, as was the case
in previous years, the games are more spread out so TNT and TBS --
the two Turner networks -- will not compete head-to-head for viewers
on weeknights.
STATS:
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Hornets won 14 of their final 16 games to gain
homecourt advantage over the Philadelphia 76ers. ... The Minnesota
Timberwolves were 50-32, the best record in franchise history. ...
The Los Angeles Lakers won 33 of their final 37 games. They will
have homecourt advantage as long as they stay alive.
STRONG AT HOME:
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern Conference-leading Indiana Pacers went 36-5 in their
new Conseco Fieldhouse -- matching the Western Conference-leading
Los Angeles Lakers for the league's top record at home.
SEASON OF FUTILITY:
</P>
<P>
   At 17-65, the 1999-00 Chicago Bulls had by far the worst record
in team history. Despite 32 more chances, they managed only four
more victories than last year's hastily assembled post-lockout
squad that barely knew each other's names. Only one other Bulls
team won less than 30 percent of its games in a full season, and
the 1975-76 squad at least managed to win 29 percent (24-58).
SPEAKING:
</P>
<P>
   ''We are subject to the gods of television, but to stretch this
out over two weeks is absolutely insane. It's losing its
competitive edge. It's allowing guys to have more preparation. It's
allowing people to almost get bored. You've made them wait all year
long, 82 games, and now you're going to make them wait two weeks to
get through five games?'' -- Miami coach Pat Riley, speaking about
the fact that the Heat's best-of-five playoff series against the
Detroit Pistons will be spread over 13 days to accommodate
television. The teams have three days off before Game 3 in Detroit,
then three more days off before Game 4, also in Detroit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
