<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Preparing for New Season  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NADEL, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers enjoyed a
wonderful regular season, winning eight more games than anyone else
in the NBA and recording the second-highest victory total in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as coach Phil Jackson points out, they're starting over,
dead even with the other 15 teams in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's just say this is one segment and we've got that over
with,'' Jackson said Thursday at the team's practice facility.
''The surprise is that we got 67 victories, which is a substantial
amount.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here it is, this is the moment we all play the games for.
There are no easy routes. There's more intensity, more pressure on
the players. We're going to climb this mountain together over the
next few weeks, and see where we go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who had winning streaks of 16, 19 and 11 games
during a 67-15 regular season, open the postseason Sunday against
the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 at Staples Center in the best-of-five first-round series
isn't until Thursday night, prompting Jackson to say, ''I believe
(the layoff) favors Sacramento, and I will tell you why; they'll be
able to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings spokesman Troy Hanson said the Kings will fly to Los
Angeles after practice Saturday and return home after Sunday's game
before flying back to Southern California on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The team enters the playoffs in relatively good health,''
Hanson added.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have played the Lakers tough this season, beating them
once and losing three times, but by only seven, one and three
points. However, Sacramento enters the postseason on a downer,
losing seven of its last eight games, including the final four.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know, maybe the pressure at the end of the season or
the injuries they had,'' Jackson said when asked his opinion on the
late-season slump. ''I know they played us well last Friday (in a
121-114 Los Angeles victory). I've got to give them credit on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers also finished the season on a losing note, falling at
Dallas and San Antonio this week, but Jackson said, ''These last
two games have no bearing on our year at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers lost three of their last six games, but that was
after they clinched the NBA's best record and homecourt advantage
throughout the playoffs. And O'Neal missed a win and a loss because
of a slightly sprained ankle that shouldn't be a problem in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a team, I think we're relatively healthy,'' Jackson said.
''We just want good physical health. I think if we can maintain
that, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, who averaged an NBA-leading 29.7 points
and 22.5 points, respectively, both have nagging injuries, but
Lakers spokesman John Black said both planned to practice today.
Jackson gave the team Thursday off.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays on Bryant's right wrist early Thursday were negative.
Black said Bryant injured his wrist in Dallas on Tuesday night and
fell on it early in Wednesday night's game in San Antonio, but
wound up scoring 23 points in 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was called for a technical foul in overtime of the
Lakers' 103-98 loss in San Antonio after turning his elbow into
David Robinson's stomach. Robinson went down, grimacing in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'd been hard fouled, hurt his shoulder again in the third
quarter,'' Jackson said of O'Neal. ''It looked like Robinson fouled
him at least two times before they called the foul. It's obvious
this league doesn't call flagrant fouls against Shaquille.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers submitted their playoff roster, which includes guard
Derek Fisher, who missed the final four regular-season games due to
a bone spur in his right ankle. Rookie John Celestand, activated
when Fisher was placed on the injured list last week, was removed
from the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's practiced limited, just shooting, the last three days,''
Jackson said. ''He'll star going all-out tomorrow. We'll need a
smaller guard at times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 0224 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milwaukee Heads for Postseason  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. FRANCIS, Wis. (AP) -- In the spring, young men's thoughts
turn to baseball -- even if those young men are getting ready for
the NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   At their plush training facility on the fog-shrouded shores of
Lake Michigan on Thursday, the Milwaukee Bucks seemed relaxed,
refreshed, ready for the postseason -- and even a little bit
preoccupied with the summer game.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, guard Rafer Alston flipped through the sports pages to
learn more about his hometown New York Yankees' eight-game winning
streak. ''They should put us in our own league!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, Tim Thomas, Robert Traylor and Danny Manning took
advantage of a break in the Bucks' day of two practices and three
hours of mandatory film study to break out their baseball mitts and
play catch on the practice floor, rolling grounders across the
polished hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just look around, see how relaxed we are,'' Thomas said. ''The
pressure is on Indiana. They're supposed to take care of us. We're
going in there with everything to gain.''
</P>
<P>
   The first game of eighth-seeded Milwaukee's playoff rematch with
the Indiana Pacers isn't until Sunday. The Bucks ended the season
with three straight victories -- matching their longest winning
streak of the year -- and 11 wins in the last 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're feeling good, we're feeling loose and we're feeling
dangerous,'' said Glenn Robinson, who has been in just three
playoff games in six years with Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the first time since I've been here, I feel like this team
can do some damage in the playoffs. We're really pumped up around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a serious rally in the season's final month for the
Bucks to leap past ninth-place Orlando and into the playoffs, but
coach George Karl has already declared the season a success for his
young, inexperienced team.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got improvement in all the areas I wanted to improve, so I
call that a success,'' said Karl, citing his team's ''increased
effort and better knowledge of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Bucks can get down to the business of challenging the
top-seeded Pacers, with whom they split their four-game season
series. Milwaukee blew out Indiana twice and was one of just five
visiting teams to win at Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's unfinished business for us down there,'' leading
scorer Ray Allen said. ''Last year, we got swept by them because we
didn't know what the playoffs were all about. This year, we know a
little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks will return home during the three days between the
first and second games at Conseco Fieldhouse. Milwaukee's first
home playoff game won't be played until April 29.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the Bucks was pleased by the NBA's TV-friendly
schedule, Allen was grateful for three more days to rest his
sprained left knee. Allen said he expects the injury to be nothing
more than a dull ache by Sunday's Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to say I'll be 100 percent, but I know I won't be,''
Allen said. ''But at the same time, it's nothing huge. It won't
prevent me from shooting or defending or doing the things I want to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more important than Allen's physical health is the
solid mental health of the team.
</P>
<P>
   After a year in which Karl publicly ripped the defensive play
and leadership of his Big Three -- Allen, Robinson and Sam Cassell --
the Bucks' leaders and their coach seem to be the picture of
domestic bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything is coming together for us at the right time,''
Cassell said. ''It's been a long road, but we're all on the same
page now. I feel good about where we're at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 0228 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands march to City Hall, voice anger at mayor  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Vowing to make sure Mayor Rudolph Giuliani does
not win his bid for the U.S. Senate, more than 2,000 protesters
marched several miles, from Brooklyn to City Hall, shouting that
the mayor has mishandled several fatal police shootings of unarmed
men. They also called for him to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Amadou Diallo! Patrick Dorismond! Malcolm Ferguson!'' shouted
the mostly Haitian-American crowd on Thursday. ''Giuliani must
go!''
</P>
<P>
   Diallo was fatally shot last year by four white police officers
-- they were acquitted of murder charges earlier this year.
Dorismond was fatally shot outside a Manhattan bar, and Ferguson
was killed during an undercover drug raid, both in March.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, Giuliani has vociferously defended the police. He
sometimes sought to shift blame for the shootings to the victims
and raised the ire of many people by releasing Dorismond's sealed
juvenile record.
</P>
<P>
   ''You all have got to vote!'' shouted Marie Dorismond,
Dorismond's sister. ''All of this will mean nothing if you don't
vote. One vote will make one big difference. I'm tired of crying
for black brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no mention by speakers at the rally that if Giuliani
loses the Senate race in November -- his Democratic opponent is
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton -- he would remain mayor until
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters also voiced anger toward the NYPD, but their
focus was Giuliani, and many signs depicted the mayor as the devil
or Adolf Hitler. The signs were cheered by about a hundred
onlookers as the marchers came off the Brooklyn Bridge into
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Giuliani violates human rights,'' ''Giuliani, the new
Hitler,'' and ''Stop and frisk Giuliani, book him up for racism,''
read some of the signs.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's office did not immediately return a telephone call
seeking comment on the signs, but at his daily press availability --
held before the marchers left Brooklyn -- the mayor mentioned the
protesters briefly.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have a right to protest, I really have no problem with
that at all as long as they do it peacefully,'' he said. ''If they
don't do it peacefully, then they also have to be ready to be
arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   The march and subsequent rally outside City Hall were peaceful,
and Dorismond's father, Andre, begged the large crowd to remain
calm. Following his son's funeral last month, a melee broke out
between some mourners and police, with injuries on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ''Keep the pressure on, keep the pressure on,'' said Dorismond,
a Haitian immigrant. ''But no violence, please. No violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond's mother, named Marie like her daughter, shouted
passionately in Creole: ''They killed my son but I didn't lose the
battle!''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered loudest for Abner Louima, the Haitian
immigrant tortured by a police officer in the bathroom of a
Brooklyn stationhouse in 1997. The soft-spoken Louima talked about
how black people are viewed by police.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are tired of being portrayed as drug dealers, we are tired
of being portrayed as criminals,'' Louima said. ''We want to be
judged for our actions, not our skin color.''
</P>
<P>
   Louima, who was flanked by a police detective as he stood on the
dais, was then led through the crowd into a car by police, who had
accompanied him to the rally. Louima has been under police
protection since his attack.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the rally was one of its organizers, the Rev. Al
Sharpton, who had a prior speaking engagement in Philadelphia.
Sharpton and his National Action Network held several rallies this
week protesting police brutality, culminating in Thursday's march
and rally. Several people, including Sharpton, were arrested at
those rallies after staging acts of civil disobedience, such as
blocking entrances to buildings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-21-00 0231 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amato May Become Italy's Premier  </HEADLINE>
By CANDACE HUGHES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Treasury Minister Giuliano Amato, nicknamed ''Dr.
Subtle'' for his skill at trimming government spending, was on
track to become Italy's next premier in an effort to avoid early
elections.
</P>
<P>
   President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi was scheduled to finish
consultations today with the nation's political leaders on a
replacement for Premier Massimo D'Alema, who resigned this week.
</P>
<P>
   The president has the option of calling a special election, but
is unlikely to do so because it would block a referendum on
reforming the electoral system that he wants to see go through.
</P>
<P>
   The center-left has promised to offer Ciampi a single candidate
to replace D'Alema. Socialist leader Enrico Boselli said Amato was
expected to get the coalition's nod. Other leftist leaders said the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, 61, was premier in 1992 and 1993 and faced a currency
crisis that forced him to devalue the lira.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, a professor of constitutional law, was expected to return
to Italy today from World Bank and International Monetary Fund
meetings in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative opposition led by media mogul Silvio Berlusconi
wants Ciampi to call elections now, a year ahead of schedule. But
in an interview with The Associated Press, the ex-premier seemed
resigned to a wait.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fear there won't be a vote until 2001,'' Berlusconi said,
complaining that the center-left would come up with a ''useful
idiot'' to run the country until then.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi insisted Italians will return him to power in the
next election despite a corruption conviction and more trials
ahead. He is also viewed with suspicion in Europe for hanging on to
a media empire while in politics.
</P>
<P>
   His conservative candidates swept to victory in eight of 15
regional races over the weekend, prompting D'Alema's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, the first ex-Communist to lead Italy, came close to
setting a record for short-lived governments in a country famous
for its ''revolving door'' leadership. He was in power 18 months
and headed both the 56th and 57th governments since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with state TV, D'Alema said Thursday he was
opposed to early elections and chastised Berlusconi for his
''useful idiot'' comment.
</P>
<P>
   ''We passed through an election campaign that was among the
ugliest in democratic history,'' D'Alema said. ''Now the campaign
is over.
</P>
<P>
   ''Berlusconi, wait a few more months.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi's loathing of leftists, whom he blames for his legal
woes, was clear throughout the hour-long interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''D'Alema has been dozens of times to Moscow. He has eaten bread
and communism at the table with his father, a Communist deputy,''
Berlusconi said.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi has been tried four times on charges ranging from
bribing tax inspectors to illegal party financing. He was convicted
three times. Two convictions were thrown out on first appeal, with
still another level of appeals left. Other cases, including one for
corruption, are pending. Berlusconi said he would be exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he has detached himself from his business empire
and let his son and daughter run it since 1994, when he was
premier.
</P>
<P>
   His alliance did well in Sunday's regional elections in part
thanks to a campaign marriage with Umberto Bossi, a volatile
regional leader known for harsh anti-immigrant pronouncements. But
Berlusconi said regulated, legal immigration would be good for
Italy, which has a low birth rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
