<HEADLINE> Testimony in Peeler case to begin May 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A judge has set May 2 as the day
testimony will begin in the trial of Russell Peeler Jr. who is
charged with murder in the shooting deaths of an 8-year-old boy and
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   But before that happens, Superior Court Judge G. Sarsfield Ford
said he will issue a written ruling on a defense motion to dismiss
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler Jr., 28, faces the possibility of the death
penalty in the Jan. 7, 1999, slayings of Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr.
and his mother, Karen Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Peeler masterminded the killings to prevent the
boy from testifying against him in an earlier murder case. Peeler's
brother, Adrian, 25, is also charged in the murders, accused of
gunning down mother and son in their Bridgeport home.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler's lawyers have asked that the charges be
dismissed because the state's key witness appears to have recanted
at least some of what she originally told police.
</P>
<P>
   In statements to police and in a videotaped deposition she gave
in November, Josephine Lee said she acted as a lookout and
witnessed the murders. But in December, she wrote a letter to her
lawyer, claiming she lied. At the same time, Lee wrote three
separate letters to Bridgeport police officers in which she
apologized for her role in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has not said if he plans to deny the motion, but instructed
his court officer, Thomas St. John, to notify the 12 jurors and six
alternates to be in court at 10 a.m. May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Ford did deny a separate motion by the state Thursday to have
opening arguments in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict contended that an opening
argument to the jury might help them understand what may be a
complicated case.
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments are very rarely done in state criminal trials and
Ford told Benedict, ''I think you have selected fair-minded people
who are capable of following the trail of the case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
