<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 03:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LA Times Agrees To Halt Ads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Times is dropping promotional
ads that juxtapose images of Muslim women in long chadors with
those of bikini-clad beachgoers after the city's Islamic community
and the newspaper's employees complained.
</P>
<P>
   The ads were part of a new campaign that attempted to contrast
images of Southern California with world events the newspaper
covers.
</P>
<P>
   They drew criticism not only from Muslims but from more than 200
Times editors and reporters who signed a petition last week
complaining that the ads were offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Other ads in the campaign contrasted an overweight man lying on
a beach with the body of a dead soldier lying in a street, and cars
on a crowded freeway with a column of tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Times spokesman Mike Lange said the beach ad will be replaced by
others previously prepared to run in rotation. He said there are no
plans to pull any of the other ads.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper agreed to withdraw the ad following discussions
with representatives of the Council on American Islamic Relations
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ''We appreciate the Times' willingness to address Muslim
concerns,'' Nihad Awad, the council's executive director, said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Times employees who signed the petition praised the company's
move, but some believed other ads in the series also should have
been withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   By highlighting differences among people, the campaign
contradicted the efforts of many reporters and editors to bring the
city's diverse population together, said reporter Lorenza Munoz.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a start,'' she said of the decision. ''I think the dead
body one is in pretty poor taste, but at least they recognize the
other was not only bad advertising and divisive, but was offensive
as well. The way the ad portrayed the Muslims, it was as if it was
us vs. them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
