<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 04:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Threats Close Several Schools  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE GUTTERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- In Ohio, a seventh-grader was arrested in a bomb
threat against her school. In Virginia, a 15-year-old girl was
arrested for allegedly making death threats against classmates on a
computer. In Wisconsin, an Army bomb squad was called to
investigate a device left in front of a high school.
</P>
<P>
   Many schools around the country canceled classes or tightened
security Thursday because of a rash of threats and rumors tied to
the anniversary of the Columbine High massacre in suburban Denver.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of violence or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   School safety experts said it was natural that threats and hoax
calls would increase on the anniversary of the deadliest school
shooting in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are more likely simply because of the awareness people
have of the Columbine anniversary,'' said Pamela Riley, president
of the Center for the Prevention of School Violence at North
Carolina State University. ''It seems like an anniversary of
something like this is a time to remember by doing something that
is good, but unfortunately, that's not what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   No threats were made against Columbine or other Jefferson County
high schools, a district spokesman said, but there was plenty of
activity elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Schools ''have all been walking the tightrope all week, trying
to keep their guard up and react to incidents and track down rumors
while at the same time not overreacting and creating the type of
situation they are trying to avoid,'' said Kenneth Trump, president
of National School Safety and Security Services, a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, Pulaski County High School was closed after a
15-year-old girl was arrested for allegedly making death threats
against her classmates on a Web page she created on a school
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Schools were closed Thursday in Port Edwards, Wis., after a
bomb-like device was found near the front doors of a high school.
An Army bomb squad determined that the device -- a propane tank with
a timer, batteries and wires -- could not have detonated.
</P>
<P>
   In Westerville, Ohio, a 13-year-old girl was arrested in a bomb
threat at Walnut Springs Middle School, where officials sent
students to a neighboring church until the time listed in the
threat had passed. Classes then resumed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
