<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 04:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New US Magazine Designed for Papers  </HEADLINE>
By VICKI BROWN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A new national magazine hopes to succeed
by filling a void for weekly and small daily newspapers looking for
an affordable, folksier alternative to Parade and USA Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   American Profile, which premieres April 23, targets community
newspaper readers with features about ''the type of people who make
up these communities and make them special,'' says Dan Hammond,
founder and CEO of Nashville-based Publishing Group of America.
</P>
<P>
   ''We recognized that major metro markets have been well served
with a plethora of media, including two well-entrenched Sunday
magazines,'' Hammond said. There was not, however, a weekly
supplement for small publishers, focusing on hometown life, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that niche was smart business, said Samir A. Husni,
a University of Mississippi journalism professor and magazine
industry expert.
</P>
<P>
   ''The magazine is filling a void for weekly and small daily
newspaper publishers with a channel that simply did not previously
exist,'' Husni said.
</P>
<P>
   The four-color magazine debuts with 1.1 million paid subscribers
to more than 250 newspapers, all with circulations under 20,000.
Publishers are free to insert American Profile into their newspaper
any day of the week, rather than just Sunday, like the larger
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond, who came up with the idea 10 years ago, asked
publishers what they wanted in a weekly magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ''They wanted it to feature a hometown each week in each region.
They wanted it to lift up and celebrate people who do extraordinary
things and ask for no recognition,'' Hammond said.
</P>
<P>
   Producing the magazine wasn't feasible until now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, we have the ability to go from computer to press and
eliminate many steps that would have been cumbersome and costly. We
can print, drop and ship,'' Hammond said.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers pay about $25 for each 1,000 circulation, plus
shipping, handling and the cost of inserting the magazine, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cover story for the first issue, ''Home for Good,'' looks at
Americans who are leaving cities for the lure of small town life.
The ''Hometown Spotlight'' feature is on Jonesboro, Ga., the town
where ''Gone With The Wind'' author Margaret Mitchell researched
historical background for her novel.
</P>
<P>
   Each issue has a national feature common to all editions. For
example, the week of July 23 will offer a guide to state fairs,
with a list of dates and entertainers. Recipes and calendar events
will vary by region.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Randolph, publisher of The Harrodsburg Herald, a 6,300
circulation weekly in Harrodsburg, Ky., was the first to contract
for American Profile.
</P>
<P>
   ''They sent a couple of copies and one had a feature on a family
dairy farm,'' said Randolph, who thought the story would appeal to
readers in his town 35 miles south of Lexington, Ky. ''It's about
the common, everyday man.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there are about 7,000 community newspapers -- weekly
or small daily newspapers with no more than a 30 percent overlap in
circulation with a larger daily.
</P>
<P>
   American Profile's target audience is readers in towns with
85,000 or below populations. Hammond has turned down larger dailies
that want to subscribe in order to keep the magazine's well-defined
market.
</P>
<P>
   The largest circulation newspaper to buy the magazine is The
Daily Sun, in Lady Lake, Fla., a city of 18,000 just outside Ocala.
The smallest has a circulation of about 1,000, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 0456 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
