<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 07:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sheriff Backs Columbine Rescuers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- The county sheriff is defending his
deputies as heroes in the wake of nine new lawsuits accusing the
department of mishandling the response and not doing enough to
prevent last year's Columbine High School shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't do anything wrong,'' Jefferson County Sheriff John
Stone said. ''We have people who did some pretty heroic things that
are now getting kicked in the face for rescuing people, for saving
people's lives -- because of greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone spoke Thursday, the one-year anniversary of the day when
two teen-age gunmen opened fire on the Littleton school, killing 12
students and a teacher before committing suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The new lawsuits were filed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In one lawsuit, the parents of slain student Daniel Rohrbough
allege he was killed by a bullet fired by a deputy. Authorities
have said no evidence exists that Rohrbough died from friendly
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawsuits contends a police sharpshooter was refused
permission to shoot one of the gunmen through a library window;
investigators did not investigate complaints of hate-filled
rhetoric on a Web page maintained by one of the killers; and
authorities disregarded pleas for help from students trying to save
teacher Dave Sanders, who later died.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said his department will be vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want this thing at some point to be put to rest,'' he
said, ''to let this community heal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
