<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 08:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Tennessee Men Accused of Fraud  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two Tennessee men have been indicted on federal
charges for allegedly buying nearly $750,000 worth of diamonds and
Rolex watches using credit card numbers stolen from some of the
nation's top executives.
</P>
<P>
   James Rinaldo Jackson, 39, and Dereck Cunningham, 28, both of
Memphis, were charged in U.S. District Court in Manhattan with
participating in a scheme to use the stolen information to buy
merchandise throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in December, the men allegedly obtained about 20
diamonds, including at least two in excess of five carats and at
least two in excess of four carats. One diamond was valued at more
than $54,000.
</P>
<P>
   Among victims of the fraud were the chief operating officer of
Coca-Cola Enterprises, the chief executive officer of Hilton Hotels
and the chairman and chief executive officer of Lehman Brothers
Holdings, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Other victims included the estates of deceased executives,
including a former chairman and chief executive officer of Wendy's
International and a former administrator of Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleged that Jackson and Cunningham purposefully
identified prominent members of the nation's business community as
targets of their scheme and then stole critical personal
information about them.
</P>
<P>
   The men impersonated their victims in telephone calls to banks
and credit card companies, convincing them to change the billing
addresses on the accounts to hotels in Tennessee, Arkansas and
Mississippi, where they later had the goods shipped, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the scheme, Jackson made reservations at the hotels
in the names of his victims and notified the hotels to expect
packages to be delivered to the individuals, the government
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was arrested by FBI agents in Memphis who watched him
try to pick up a package addressed to one of his victims at a
Memphis-area hotel, prosecutors said. Jackson was being held
without bail pending further court proceedings in New York. His
lawyer did not immediately return a phone message for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham has not yet been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Jackson and Cunningham each face maximum sentences
of 30 years in prison and $1 million fines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 0821 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
