<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 09:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W.African Leaders OK Same Currency  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACCRA, Ghana (AP) -- Six West African nations have signed an
agreement to share a common currency within three years.
</P>
<P>
   The countries that signed Thursday's agreement are Ghana,
Nigeria, Liberia, Sierra Leone, Gambia and Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   The joint declaration came at a summit of leaders of the West
African economic community.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have taken a giant leap forward. We are doing what we
should have done some time back but ... better late than never,''
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo said.
</P>
<P>
   The signatories pledged to immediately create a regional central
bank and reduce annual inflation to five percent by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration also suggests a possible monetary union with
eight other West African countries that already share a
French-backed currency, the CFA franc.
</P>
<P>
   Those nations are Ivory Coast, Senegal, Burkina Faso, Mali,
Niger, Togo, Benin and Guinea-Bissau.
</P>
<P>
   Another six central African nations share a currency also called
the CFA franc which is linked to, but separate from, the West
African unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 0909 </TRAILER>
