<HEADLINE> Tentative Northwest Deal Reached  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- Northwest Airlines flight attendants will
decide whether to ratify a tentative five-year contract to end a
bitter 3{-year battle with the nation's fourth-largest carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots will be mailed next week to the airline's 11,000 flight
attendants, who rejected a tentative agreement last August. They
have been seeking a new contract since September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hallelujah,'' said attendant Dara Manuel at Minneapolis-St.
Paul International Airport when she learned of the tentative pact
reached Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's exciting. It's really exciting. This has been a long,
uphill battle, a long negotiation process. I'm thankful that it's
probably, hopefully, coming to end,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Steenland, Northwest executive vice president and chief
corporate officer, called the agreement ''a fair one for all
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters Local 2000 President Billie Davenport said the union
wouldn't release details until its executive board had a chance to
review the pact and send it to members.
</P>
<P>
   But a statement posted on the union's Web site gave the
following details:
</P>
<P>
   --Industry-leading pension rates, increased from $35 to $65 per
month per year of service, nearly an 86 percent improvement.
</P>
<P>
   --Increased base pay with ''date of signing'' increases of 8
percent to 27.7 percent, depending on longevity. Attendants with
the least seniority would get the biggest raises because there is a
wider gap in pay between new hires at Northwest and the rest of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   --Stronger work rules.
</P>
<P>
   --Full domestic partner health insurance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, pay for Northwest flight attendants starts at around
$15,000 and rises to more than $40,000, with the average pay in the
mid-$30,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have remained high since Northwest sued the union over
an alleged holiday sickout. Northwest fired 18 flight attendants
for calling in sick during the Christmas-New Year's holiday period,
and the union filed grievances. About 300 flights were canceled
over the period.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides had agreed before Thursday that the company's lawsuit
would be dropped if the flight attendants ratified a tentative
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants took pay cuts for three years beginning in
1993 to help keep Northwest out of bankruptcy, and until early this
year wages were only 3 percent higher than before the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Northwest gave flight attendants a 4 percent raise,
just a day after giving its mechanics, custodians and cleaners the
same pay increase.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest pilots went on a 15-day strike in 1998 that crippled
the airline for weeks and cost the company millions in lost
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
