<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit-Lyonnais May Be Disciplined  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese regulators recommended disciplinary action
Friday against the Tokyo branch of Credit Lyonnais Securities
Europe-Swiss AG, accusing the company of violations involving
customer accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Surveillance Commission submitted
the recommendation to Japan's Financial Reconstruction Commission,
alleging that the brokerage firm violated the law in three separate
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the company's office in Tokyo could not be reached
after office hours Friday for comment on the decision. The
company's media office in Paris had already closed until Tuesday
for the Easter holiday as well.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the SESC said that Credit Lyonnais Securities
illegally provided around $6,040 in property gains on Feb. 1 to
artificially boost a customer's profits.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also said the brokerage solicited a customer in
January 1998 for a securities index futures transaction by
promising profits and saying that it would cover any loss from the
brokerage firm's own accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The third incident occurred in September 1998 when the
commission said the firm falsified reports sent to a customer over
a stock options transaction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1023 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland To Probe Financial Leak  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Acting on the request of Poland's central
bank, prosecutors launched an investigation Friday into a report
that a decision to raise key interest rates in February was leaked
to some investors.
</P>
<P>
   Julita Sobczak, spokeswoman for Warsaw prosecutors, said the
course of the investigation would be kept secret ''because of the
nature of the information and its importance for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank officials said earlier this month that their decision to
raise key interest rates Feb. 23 had been leaked a few hours in
advance and had called for an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rising inflation, most analysts had not expected the
move because of a boost in key rates in November.
</P>
<P>
   Poland's largest daily newspaper, Gazeta Wyborcza, has reported
that one investment bank made big deals in Polish currency just
hours before the decision was announced at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Exclusive advance knowledge of rate increases, which effectively
raise the cost of borrowing throughout the economy, could allow
currency traders to reap big profits at the expense of others who
don't expect rate changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1024 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
