<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Plunge, Others Closed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian markets were idle Friday for Easter
holidays but in Tokyo the key stock index plunged on technical
factors.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average tumbled
706.64 points, or 3.7 percent, to 18,252.68. On Thursday, it closed
down 127.30 points, or 0.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Nikkei opened higher, boosted by a rally overnight on Wall
Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 169.09, or 1.6
percent, to close at 10,844.05.
</P>
<P>
   But Tokyo investors later began selling industrial stocks which
will be removed from the Nikkei index starting April 24.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty of the index's stocks will be replaced to better reflect
changes in Japan's economy, the Nihon Keizai newspaper, a major
Japanese financial daily and the administrator of the index, said
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Removal of stocks from the index tends to lower their prestige
and makes them less attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 105.68 yen,
up 0.90 yen from 104.78 yen late Thursday but slightly below its
late New York level of 105.73 yen overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Thai shares closed higher in thin trading. The Stock Exchange of
Thailand's Composite Index rose 5.58 points, or 1.4 percent, to
close at 395.06.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices in Taiwan ended slightly higher for the second
straight session in response to overnight gains in U.S. stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Taipei market's Weighted Stock Price Index gained 8.59
points, or 0.09 percent, to 9,117.64.
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, the Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 5.91
points, or 0.7 percent, to 767.16.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysian shares closed mixed amid continuing investor caution
about the future direction of U.S. markets. The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange's Composite Index gained 3.71 points, or 0.41 percent, to
898.98.
</P>
<P>
   Markets were closed in Hong Kong, Australia, New Zealand, the
Philippines, Singapore, and Indonesia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1049 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
