<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alaskan Senate OKs Cruise Ship Tax  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL QUEARY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) -- The Alaska Senate has approved a bill that
would require cruise ships to pay a $50 tax on each passenger they
bring into Alaska waters.
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed 14-6 Thursday, a day after it surfaced in a
late- night Senate committee hearing amid wrangling over how to
regulate the cruise industry. It now goes to the House, where its
future is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Halford, a Republican, argued that the profitable and
mostly foreign-owned cruise ships pay little to operate in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is all of Alaska for $50,'' he said. ''They are selling
Alaska and we are giving them Alaska to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   But other senators cited concerns about the bill's fairness and
the possible impact on tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the tax-and-spenders put this together, why weren't the
airline passengers, ferry passengers and recreation vehicle drivers
considered?'' remarked Senate Majority Leader Jerry Mackie, also a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The tax would bring in more than $30 million from the more than
600,000 cruise ship passengers who visit the state each year.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise ship industry has opposed smaller head taxes such as
the $5 fee approved by Juneau voters last fall. Industry officials
contend cruise ships already pay their way through port fees and
sales taxes paid by passengers in various communities.
</P>
<P>
   The head tax was drafted by the Senate Finance Committee late
Wednesday, grafting it onto legislation requiring regular
disclosures from cruise ships about what they release into Alaska
waters.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would displace local taxes such as Juneau's, but $5
would be kicked back to the local government in each port town a
passenger visited. That would funnel money to small ports that have
hesitated to impose taxes out of fear the ships would bypass them
as punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The money the state gets from the tax would be earmarked for the
operation of state-owned ports and harbors.
</P>
<P>
   The measure emerged after Republican Senate President Drue
Pearce accused cruise industry lobbyists of killing her bill to
bring cruise ships and other large vessels under the state's oil
spill response laws. Though still alive, Pearce's bill is stalled
in the House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1112 </TRAILER>
