<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York reaching for future grapples with past  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BAINBRIDGE, N.Y. (AP) -- In a small town, government officials
and archeologists are carefully reburying human bone fragments that
may date to 30 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, a city like many in the Northeast's Rust Belt,
developers find its hard to turn a shovel of dirt without exposing
windows to the past.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the issue is a recurring one where European
settlements date to the 1600s and American Indian civilizations
date back thousands of years before that. The goal of historic
preservation often conflicts with the needs -- and deadlines -- of
development.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the conflict is played out in several parts of
upstate New York where recovering from recession and a lost
industrial base is often Job One.
</P>
<P>
   In Bainbridge, 26 miles northeast of Binghamton, human remains
that could date to 30 B.C. will be reburied during a June 17
ceremony with Onondaga and Oneida tribal representatives, officials
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The bone fragments are believed to be those of a child. Other
artifacts were uncovered by a Binghamton University archaeological
team headed by Nina Versaggi. They were found in a small wetlands
park.
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts became an issue when the town wanted to build a
small dam to keep water in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The project required archaeological investigations. Thirty pits
were dug and the artifacts that were found were taken to the state
university for analysis. One was an apparent 2,000-year-old fire
pit, often a hotbed for archaeological finds.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany this week, a small piece of a century-old potter's
field has been unearthed behind an old National Guard armory.
That's where a major project called University Heights is being
built.
</P>
<P>
   The four reasonably well-preserved coffins remain, reburied, on
the site. Their uncovering was no great surprise because old maps
show that the site had once been Almshouse Square, or,
unofficially, the county poor farm.
</P>
<P>
   Historians know that approximately 1,875 bodies are on the land
behind the armory and the David Axelrod Institute of Public Health,
which includes the former drill field and tennis courts of a
private school that recently relocated to the suburbs. And that's
counting only the bodies buried from 1880 to 1920. There could have
been other burial sites in Almshouse Square, which was established
in 1820.
</P>
<P>
   The development will include a hotel, convention and retail
center. The aim is to create a new focal point for the city settled
by the Dutch in the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman John McEneny, D-Albany, believes the same
standards should be applied to marked and unmarked graves as
American Indian burial sites, which are protected by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the discovery of Indian remains on construction
sites, McEneny said, ''everything comes to a halt, and things are
done right.'' That does not always happen at other burial sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-21-00 1317 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0083 </DOCNO>
