<HEADLINE> Rolling your own is the way to save for some cigarette smokers  </HEADLINE>
n0776nyny-
r n AM-NY--MakingCigarettes Bjt   04-21 0602
AM-NY--Making Cigarettes, Bjt,597   
Rolling your own is the way to save for some cigarette smokers   
Eds: moving on news and financial wires
AP Photo
AP Membership Enterprise, 
By THOM RANDALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENS FALLS, N.Y. (AP) -- Motivated by price increases, more
smokers are adopting a practice common in the 1800s -- making their
own cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no way I want to pay $4 per pack,'' said Thomas
Fleming of Argyle. ''This cuts my cost to about $1 per pack, it
tastes good, and it burns longer and tastes better than a regular
cigarette.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco retailers in the Glens Falls area reported a four-fold
increase in sales to people who buy tobacco and craft their own
cigarettes to save as much as three-quarters of the price of
manufactured cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Although people traditionally rolled tobacco into a cigarette
paper to make their own, now more and more homemade cigarettes are
being made by packing the tobacco into a pre-formed paper tube,
complete with a filter, retailers reported.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming has been packing his own cigarettes for about a week,
after deciding to take action to cut the cost of his cigarette
smoking. He was alarmed by the $11.10-per-carton increase in state
taxes, which sent the cost of 10 packs above $40.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming used to just open a new pack to start the day before
leaving for work.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he gets up a little earlier, sets out his cigarette machine
beside his cup of coffee, and packs about 20 cigarettes -- a day's
worth.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guys at work are amazed, they ask -- 'You rolled those?
How did you do that?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saving $1,000 annually is Fleming's motive, he said. But also,
he gets to custom blend his own smoke, creating the right taste
with just enough menthol.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Blair, manager of Cigarettes Cheaper, said that just
after the March 1 tax increase, the store's sales of make-your-own
supplies and tobacco quadrupled, and it is growing week by week as
people tell others of the advantages of homemade over manufactured
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sales of cigarette packing supplies have increased
drastically since the tax increase,'' Blair said. ''Some people
think they can't make a good cigarette, but after they try, they
find out it's easy, and they can make one that tastes close to the
manufactured brand they are used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Strodel of D&AMP;G Hardware in Warrensburg said sales of
make-your-own supplies have boomed since the tax increase.
Three-quarters of his store's revenue comes from cigarettes, and a
growing portion of that is from homemade cigarette supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Underwood, a clerk at Broad Street Discount Cigarettes in
Glens Falls, also reported spiraling sales of cigarette tubes and
bulk tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ''Making your own is a fast-growing trend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes Cheaper stocks about 12 blends of tobacco, about 15
varieties of cigarette tubes -- including light and full-flavored
filters -- and several styles of packing and rolling machines.
</P>
<P>
   Machines cost from about $5 to $33, and the store has been
selling 20 to 30 machines per week, clerk Lelajo Taylor estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Shamaine Robaire of Queensbury said she likes to choose what
goes into her cigarettes, including the opportunity to buy tobacco
without additives, preservatives or fillers.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a health benefit, she figures. Since she and her
husband have been making their own, they've slashed the number of
cigarettes they smoke from nearly three packs per day each to about
one, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're more satisfying, they burn slower and I don't feel
like I need as many,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-21-00 1318 </TRAILER>
