<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Demand for Cars Runs High  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE, AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Neither falling stocks nor rising gas prices nor
higher interest rates seem to keep Americans from buying new cars
and trucks at a blistering pace.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives say their sales are still running high despite
the stunning freefall in stocks earlier this month. Sales also have
survived the run-up in gas prices, even for the gas-thirsty pickups
and sport utility vehicles. And the five interest rate increases
from the Federal Reserve since June, and the prospect of more to
come, have had little to no effect.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for the first three months of this year ran at a faster
pace than last year, when the industry was building to a record of
16.9 million cars and light trucks. Industry economists had
predicted a slight slowing of sales, but most have now revised
their estimates for 2000, saying it will equal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   David L. Littman, chief economist with Comerica Bank in Detroit,
said there is no shortage of reasons why auto sales are staying
strong. Jobs are plentiful, with the government reporting this past
week that new claims for unemployment benefits had hit a 27-year
low. Consumer confidence has stayed high; the Conference Board's
Consumer Confidence Index hit a new high in January, although it
has retreated a bit since then.
</P>
<P>
   Littman also says record profit-sharing checks for employees at
major American automakers and a 13 percent growth in tax refunds
increased the amount of cash people had to spend in the first three
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   And automakers have turned to cost reduction as a major source
of profit, keeping price increases equal to or less than inflation.
The market has become so competitive on price that rebates and
incentives have grown this year and automakers have absorbed some
interest rate increases instead of passing them to consumers
through finance deals.
</P>
<P>
   The result, according to Littman, can be seen in Comerica's auto
affordability index, which measures how many weeks of median family
income it takes to buy a car. Littman said the index stands at 23.8
weeks -- the least in 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   Another tool Littman uses to forecast the auto industry is
growth in disposable personal income. Last year, when that
statistic predicted a record year, Littman didn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ''This year, it's looking fundamentally the same,'' he said.
''It's saying auto sales will be up from last year's total.''
</P>
<P>
   While the run-up in stock prices has helped auto sales, the
''wealth effect'' from investments is weaker than personal income
or prices, Littman said. It has the most effect on the luxury end
of the market, and as a psychological measure of economic health.
</P>
<P>
   ''But if (the stock market) had continued plunging, it would
have affected general retail and by extension automobiles within
one quarter,'' Littman said.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers contend there's yet another reason for strong sales.
Foreign companies have targeted the U.S. market, shipping in new
models. Meanwhile, General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and
DaimlerChrysler AG have been trying to reduce the amount of design
time a new model takes.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a faster turnover of models and a wider variety.
Several new models have seen far more demand than supply, including
the Chrysler PT Cruiser and the Nissan Xterra. Ford keeps the plant
that builds its full-size SUVs running around the clock, and says
that many of its truck models are selling out.
</P>
<P>
   ''The combination of good economic times, high consumer
confidence, strong product development and prices that are as low
as they have been in the past 20 years has resulted in very strong
demand,'' Ford chief executive Jac Nasser said.
</P>
<P>
   Even automakers on the higher end say they're not feeling
worried about the market jitters. Lexus said Thursday that its
inventories were still very low. The company has a 9-day supply of
some models, when 60 days is the industry norm.
</P>
<P>
   After the stock market plunge on Friday, April 14, ''we had a
great weekend,'' Bryan Bergsteinsson, Lexus Group vice president
and general manager, said Thursday. ''People were showing up and
buying cars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
