<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Duo Works Hard for Riches  </HEADLINE>
By GREG MYRE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Customers stream into the Kuong Ngan
motorbike shop from morning to night, plop down stacks of $100
bills and speed off on shiny new Hondas, adding several decibels
and a bit more congestion to Hanoi's frenetic streets.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam's wheezing state-run economy continues to putter in low
gear despite limited market reforms that have slowly opened it up.
The roaring success of Kuong Ngan underscores the Southeast Asian
nation's vast potential but unrealized growth.
</P>
<P>
   Owners Dang Thi Ngan, 42, and her husband, Khuc Manh Kuong, 48,
are among the small number of Vietnamese who have struck it rich
under ''doi moi,'' the economic renovation process that began in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   The open-air shop at one of Hanoi's busiest intersections has
turnover that just about any Western business would envy -- an
average of 70 motorbikes a day at around $2,000 each, according to
Ngan. There's no credit, and at 14,000 to the dollar, it would take
a suitcase full of Vietnamese dong to buy a bike, so most customers
use $100 U.S. bills that they hoard against inflation -- this in a
country where the average annual income is $370.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are the biggest shop in Hanoi,'' said Ngan, a smartly
dressed woman with two gold necklaces, six rings and several
bracelets jangling from wrists and ankles. ''We don't need to
advertise because everyone knows us by reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's gotten much easier to open a business, but it still takes
a lot of hard work to make it a success.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple's tale illustrates the challenges of doing business
under a communist government that officially favors market reforms
but fears yielding control.
</P>
<P>
   They opened the modest shop in 1989, buying up used motorbikes
one at a time, mostly from government officials who were among the
few people with money and access to goods made abroad.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, cheap bicycles dominated Hanoi's then-tranquil
streets. Today, motorbikes rule the road, converging on traffic
circles like a swarm of angry hornets. A decade hence, small cars
likely will clog the tree-lined boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   The shop is open 12 hours a day, seven days a week, and either
Ngan or her husband is always present. The two employ 55 people and
are actively looking for foreign partners to provide expansion
capital and to offer managerial expertise, virtually nonexistent in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Several shops they opened in outlying provinces failed because
it was hard to find good managers, Ngan said, and most people in
smaller towns opt for cheaper motorbikes like Soviet Minsks that
sell for maybe a quarter of the cost of the Hondas.
</P>
<P>
   The bustling Hanoi shop has given the couple a large new house,
a big Mercedes -- and an ever-expanding workload. Their last brief
vacation was three years ago. Their only immediate ambition is to
get their 18-year-old daughter into an American university after
she graduates from high school this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still in the process of expanding our business,'' Ngan
said. ''Maybe in the future we will have time to relax.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1337 </TRAILER>
