<DOCNO> APW20000421.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Gather at Targeted Temple  </HEADLINE>
By WILFRIED GLOEDE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ERFURT, Germany (AP) -- Germans laid flowers and held a vigil
Friday outside a small synagogue after it was targeted in an
attempted arson attack, possibly by neo-Nazis angry that police had
broken up a party celebrating Adolf Hitler's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask myself what kind of kids these are who would do such a
thing,'' said Manfred Ruge, mayor of the eastern city of Erfurt,
where the attack happened late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This cannot be excused,'' he said, noting that Passover
celebrations had just been held in the building.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers threw a glass bottle filled with diesel fuel at
the back wall of the synagogue just after 10 p.m. Police said the
fuel spilled onto a footpath and the flames were quickly stomped
out by residents. The building was undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   A note was found about 100 yards from the scene claiming the
attack was anti-Semitic and signed with ''Heil Hitler!''
</P>
<P>
   A short time before, police had broken up what they described as
a ''Hitler party'' in a nearby street because illegal Nazi symbols
were observed. German authorities are on heightened alert each year
on April 20 -- Hitler's birthday -- for neo-Nazi gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one people were briefly taken into custody from the
party, and police said some had been released before the attack and
were being investigated. Police also were reviewing a videotape
from a security camera installed on the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   But at an afternoon news conference, state police director Peter
Werner said they had been unable to make out any suspects from that
group. Although far-right extremists were still considered the most
likely suspects, he said investigators had not ruled anything out.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Silke Becker said the computer-printed claim of
responsibility was not exactly consistent with a spontaneous
attack. Police also noted that it included a German word usually
used by left-wing radicals as an insult for neo-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, German government spokesman Uwe-Karsten Heye
condemned the ''cowardly attack'' and called for quick action to
arrest those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The synagogue in Erfurt, capital of Thuringia state, was the
first rebuilt in East Germany after World War II. Finished in 1952,
it replaced one that had been burned to the ground by the Nazis
during the 1938 Kristallnacht pogrom, or ''Night of Broken Glass.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor visited the synagogue Friday to meet with Jewish
community leaders, including state chairman Wolfgang Nossen, who
called for stronger action against right-wing violence. Thuringia,
an economically depressed state of 2.5 million people, has a Jewish
community of only about 600.
</P>
<P>
   A stream of Erfurt residents stopped by the synagogue throughout
the day, a public holiday because of Christian Good Friday
observances. Several laid bouquets of roses and spring flowers in
front of the building.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm here to show solidarity,'' said Thomas-Michael Austel, a
Lutheran priest. He added that the attack was particularly shocking
because it came in a year that the week of Passover overlaps
Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, police in western Hesse state said Friday they had
arrested 46 people celebrating Hitler's birthday at two neo-Nazi
parties Thursday night. Most were held only temporarily, although
seven were jailed overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities confiscated banned neo-Nazi flags, swastika
stickers, music CDs and cassettes as well as hashish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
