<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones To Head Harvard Press Center  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist Alex
S. Jones has been named director of the Joan Shorenstein Center on
the Press, Politics and Public Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The host of the PBS show ''Media Matters,'' Jones is a
fourth-generation journalist who has made a specialty of covering
the media.
</P>
<P>
   He covered the news industry for The New York Times from 1983 to
1992, where he won a Pulitzer Prize in 1987 for coverage of the
collapse of the Bingham family's journalism empire in Louisville,
Ky.
</P>
<P>
   The Shorenstein center, part of the John F. Kennedy School of
Government at Harvard University, is a think tank dedicated to the
study of how the media, politics and public policy interact. It
seeks to bridge the gap between journalists, scholars and the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 53, will join the Kennedy School in July. He currently
shares a chair in journalism at Duke University with his wife,
Susan Tifft. Last year, the couple co-authored ''The Trust: The
Private and Powerful Family Behind The New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really excited about it,'' Jones said. ''The Shorenstein
Center's job is illuminating the way the press affects politics and
public policy. I don't think there's ever been a time when it's
more important to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Patterson, acting director of the center, said Jones was
chosen because of his ''moral authority'' in the area of
professional ethics and for his ability to bridge academics and
professional journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need someone comfortable in both worlds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been both a reporter and a media critic within the press,
then in addition has some academic background wtih his time at
Duke,'' Patterson said. ''All of those things came together in a
way that says this is someone who has nearly the ideal background
for someone to direct the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones will succeed Marvin Kalb, the former network newsman, who
stepped down as Shorenstein director last year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.ksg.harvard.edu/presspol/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
