<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Friday, April 21, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Report: Bank One Subject of Probe
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Bank One Corp. is reported to be under
investigation by federal regulators for possible violations
involving its creation in 1998. The Wall Street Journal said today
that the regulatory arm of the National Association of Securities
Dealers is investigating Banc One Capital Markets, Bank One's
investment-banking unit. The report said the problems surfaced
after the merger of the Midwest's two biggest banks -- Columbus,
Ohio-based Banc One Corp. and First Chicago NBD Corp. -- creating
Chicago-headquartered Bank One, the nation's fifth-biggest bank.
Among the areas reportedly being investigated are account
reconciliation and bookkeeping problems.
</P>
<P>
   W. African Leaders OK Same Currency
</P>
<P>
   ACCRA, Ghana (AP) -- Six West African nations have signed an
agreement to share a common currency within three years. The
countries that signed the agreement are Ghana, Nigeria, Liberia,
Sierra Leone, Gambia and Guinea. The signatories pledged to
immediately create a regional central bank and reduce annual
inflation to five percent by 2003. The declaration also suggests a
possible monetary union with eight other West African countries
that already share a French-backed currency, the CFA franc.
</P>
<P>
   Software Group Knocks Italy Ruling
</P>
<P>
   TURIN, Italy (AP) -- An international association of leading
software manufacturers today sharply criticized an Italian judge's
ruling that it is no crime to duplicate software for personal use.
''We are extremely worried about the implications this sentence may
have,'' said Claudia Pavoletti, head of Business Software
Alliance's Italian branch. Under Italian law, one judge's decision
does not necessarily serve as precedent for similar cases. BSA said
it will keep seeking damages in court in all cases of illegal
duplication.
</P>
<P>
   Alaskan Senate OKs Cruise Ship Tax
</P>
<P>
   JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) -- The Alaska Senate has approved a bill that
would require cruise ships to pay a $50 tax on each passenger they
bring into Alaska waters. The measure now goes to the House, where
its future is uncertain. Sen. Rick Halford, a Republican, argued
that the profitable and mostly foreign-owned cruise ships pay
little to operate in the state. ''This is all of Alaska for $50,''
he said. ''They are selling Alaska and we are giving them Alaska to
sell.'' But other senators cited concerns about the bill's fairness
and the possible impact on tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Tenn. Won't Appeal Insurance Case
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The state Department of Commerce and
Insurance says it won't appeal the loss of accreditation resulting
from bungled supervision. Instead, the state has requested another
review this August and feels confident that the accreditation
committee will find that the department has adequately remedied its
problems. Tennessee Insurance Commissioner Anne Pope stated the
state's position in a letter yesterday to the National Association
of Insurance Commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   China Hospital Shows Surgery on Net
</P>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A Beijing hospital showed open-heart surgery live
on the Internet today, letting Web surfers watch a 57-year-old man
undergo a triple bypass. The 2{-hour Webcast, meant to educate the
public about heart disease, was the first of its kind in China, the
Fuwai Cardiovascular Disease Hospital said. Grainy Web images
alternated between an overhead view of the operating room and
close-ups of surgeons cutting and stitching blood vessels around
the beating heart. A hospital spokeswoman said the surgery was
successful.
</P>
<P>
   Poland To Probe Financial Leak
</P>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Polish prosecutors have launched an
investigation today into a report that a decision to raise key
interest rates in February was leaked to some investors. The
central bank asked for the probe. Julita Sobczak, spokeswoman for
Warsaw prosecutors, said the course of the investigation would be
kept secret ''because of the nature of the information and its
importance for the country.'' Bank officials said earlier this
month that their decision to raise key interest rates Feb. 23 had
been leaked a few hours in advance and had called for an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Credit-Lyonnais Might Be Disciplined
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese regulators today recommended disciplinary
action against the Tokyo branch of Credit Lyonnais Securities
Europe-Swiss AG, accusing the company of violations involving
customer accounts. The Securities and Exchange Surveillance
Commission submitted the recommendation to Japan's Financial
Reconstruction Commission, alleging that the brokerage firm
violated the law in three separate incidents. Officials at the
company's office in Tokyo could not be reached after office hours
Friday for comment on the decision.
</P>
