<HEADLINE> Arafat Aide Affirms Peace Demands  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the Middle East peace process facing
''the moment of truth,'' a top Palestinian official said Friday a
state envisioned by Chairman Yasser Arafat must include all of the
West Bank, Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem, areas captured by Israel
in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is going to be a Palestinian state along the June 4,
1967, boundaries, with East Jerusalem as its capital next to
Israel,'' said Saeb Erekat, a Palestinian negotiator who
accompanied Arafat to Washington to meet with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Territorial concessions that Israel is prepared to make are far
more modest than those foreseen by Erekat. On Thursday, the State
Department said agreement is possible only if both sides are
prepared to settle for less than their maximum demands.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat spoke at a news conference that was to have been held by
Arafat. Erekat said Arafat was tied up in discussions with
Palestinian colleagues that grew out of Arafat's Thursday meeting
with Clinton. The president met last week with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton was satisfied
with both discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the president felt the meetings of the last two weeks
with the leaders face to face were very productive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat admitted that given the differences with Israel on
territorial and other problems, a new round of negotiations opening
this month ''is not going to be an easy process.''
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the talks will be in the region and will be
April 30-May 12.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have set a Sept. 13 target date for resolution of
all issues, including the status of Jerusalem, settlements,
borders, refugees and water.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know the difficulty of the issues,'' Erekat said. ''We know
that we are at the moment of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Erekat cautioned Israel against renewed settlement activity.
''We should work in an atmosphere devoid of any unilateral steps,
any unilateral actions that may reflect negatively on the
atmosphere required to achieve agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat expressed confidence that Clinton ''will exert every
effort'' to help the parties reach a comprehensive settlement.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said ''a tough piece
of business'' lies ahead for the two sides, but the administration
believes ''there is new momentum and a new resolve'' to come to an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Abdel Rahman, the Palestine Liberation Organization
representative in Washington, said U.N. Security Council Resolution
242 will be the basis for Palestinian territorial demands.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution requires Israel to withdraw from occupied
territories.
</P>
<P>
   Rahman said agreements with Israel specify clearly the coming
negotiations should lead to implementation of 242.
</P>
<P>
   Present for the upcoming negotiations will be Ambassador Dennis
Ross, special envoy for the Middle East, and his deputy, Aaron
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the two will be ''looking to expand those elements
where there is common ground, and doing that by pushing each side
to fully explain their position, to focus on the practical and not
the theoretical, and see how far they can get.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the NET:
</P>
<P>
   State Department: www.state.gov/www/regions/nea/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
