<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers: Get Troops Out of Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Uneasy over the prospect of an
open-ended peacekeeping mission, visiting American lawmakers urged
U.N. administrators Friday to schedule local elections as soon as
possible to speed the day when foreign troops can go home.
</P>
<P>
   Elections would be the first step in establishing a functioning
government in this southern Serbian province, which has been
administered by the United Nations and NATO since Yugoslav forces
withdrew in June after the 78-day Western bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know it is going to be absolutely essential that people here
create a government that functions because countries can't keep
this number of troops here indefinitely,'' Sen. Jeff Sessions,
R-Ala., said after meeting with the senior U.N. administrator,
Bernard Kouchner.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner, a former French Cabinet minister, made no comment
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Many NATO officers here have said privately they believe
peacekeepers will have to remain in Kosovo for years before they
can leave behind a province with any chance of stability.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, two separate gunbattles in the volatile region along
Kosovo's boundary with Serbia proper killed two people and left two
policemen injured, the independent Beta News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority wants independence from Serbia
-- the larger of the two remaining Yugoslav republics. The United
States and its allies oppose full independence, as does Belgrade,
which would probably try to reassert control if peacekeepers leave.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions, however, warned that with an election this year in the
United States, there would be pressure to reduce U.S. participation
in peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is going to be pressure, and we need to bring them
home,'' he said, referring to the troops. ''This country needs to
be on its feet as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the delegation, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,
R-Texas, said the group had come to the Balkans ''to see what the
progress is for the formation of a stable government, and hopefully
the beginning of democratic elections.''
</P>
<P>
   After visiting U.S. troops, the delegation flew to Croatia,
where they met the country's president and prime minister to
discuss military and economic cooperation. The delegation will
spend Easter Sunday with American troops in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Local elections are expected this fall, but no date has been
set. On Friday, an international official said Kosovo Serbs failed
to participate in initial efforts to register the population.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting U.S. troops, the congressional delegation flew to
Croatia, where they met the country's president and prime minister
to discuss military and economic cooperation. The delegation will
spend Easter Sunday with American troops in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for local elections in Kosovo, but they are
expected later this year. U.N. officials have mixed views about the
prospect of elections in a backward area still recovering from the
effects of the 18-month Serb-Albanian conflict that prompted U.N.
and NATO intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Elections would confer legitimacy on a new set of local leaders
and settle rival claims of leadership by groups loyal to former
Kosovo Liberation Army leader Hashim Thaci and others allied with
his rival, moderate Ibrahim Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   However, elections could also widen the gap between ethnic
Albanians who want independence for Kosovo and minority Serbs, many
of whom may boycott the balloting because of their loyalty to
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Elections could also trigger violence within the factious ethnic
Albanian community as would-be leaders compete for power.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, many in the U.S. Congress see voting as a first
step toward ending a peacekeeping operation that they supported
only reluctantly -- even though American troops are without doubt
the most popular among the overwhelmingly Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am personally encouraged by the steps toward democracy and
the planning for elections that will occur on a local level in the
months ahead,'' said Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There are 37,000 NATO-led peacekeepers in Kosovo, including
5,900 Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
