<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Victory statue stolen from Brooklyn park  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- You've heard of victory being snatched from the
jaws of defeat. In this version, ''Victory'' -- all 1,000 pounds of
it -- was snatched from a Brooklyn park.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot-tall bronze statue honoring Brooklyn's fallen
soldiers of World War I was discovered missing Thursday from
Saratoga Square Park. A blow torch apparently was used to remove
Victory from its 10-foot-wide by nearly three-foot-tall base in the
middle of the park that occupies one square block.
</P>
<P>
   ''That statue commemorated the war dead, the people from that
neighborhood, the young men who had been killed defending the
freedom of that area,'' Parks Department Commissioner Henry Stern
said Friday. ''And now in the year 2000 the statue commemorating
them and honoring their sacrifice is just stolen. It's like being
killed all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have no suspects so far, and believe the thieves were
going to melt the statue down and sell it. It's believed the statue
was snatched either late Wednesday night or early Thursday morning.
Park employees noticed the statue was gone about 8:30 a.m.
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The statue is valued at about $100,000 and had stood undisturbed
since 1921. It was sculpted by James Novelli and cast by Roman
Bronze Works in Greenpoint, Brooklyn. The statue depicts a woman
with her right arm raised and her left arm holding a shield with
''E pluribus unum'' -- Latin for ''Out of many, one.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, several bronze plates listing the names of Brooklyn men
who were killed during the war was stolen, Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   He does not believe whoever stole Victory was responsible for
removing the Peter Pan statue from its pedestal in Manhattan's Carl
Schurz Park in 1998. The statue was fished out of the East River
several months later and returned to its rightful place.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a prank,'' Stern said of the Peter Pan theft. ''This
here is more serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with information regarding the Victory statue is asked to
call the Parks Department at (800) 201-PARK.
</P>
<P>
   Police also have other statue crimes to solve as well -- who's
behind the desecration of religious statues at Catholic churches
and other such institutions in Brooklyn? Police officials would not
comment if they thought the vandalized statues and the Victory
theft were connected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-21-00 1605 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0114 </DOCNO>
