<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New lawsuits claim Millstone nuclear plants killing fish  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STONINGTON, Conn. (AP) -- Fishermen Al Maderia and Tim Medeiros
are fed up -- sick of being over-regulated and tired of being blamed
for the decline of winter flounder in Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The real culprit for the flounder problem, they say, rests with
the Millstone nuclear power plants in Waterford.
</P>
<P>
   The plants suck in billions of gallons of water a day from
Niantic Bay for their cooling systems, killing off baby fish and
trapping larger fish in intake screens, the fishermen claim.
</P>
<P>
   They said Friday they are suing the plants' operator, Northeast
Utilities, for $12 million to reimburse them for damage to their
livelihoods and for the grief they've gone through with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fishermen have been blamed for it -- time and time again --
for overfishing, and we're tired of it,'' Medeiros said. ''It's
time we pointed the finger in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   This lawsuit and another claim filed by antinuclear groups and
environmental groups seek to shut down the plants or to curtail
operation during the winter flounder spawning season, now underway.
</P>
<P>
   NU spokesman Joseph Bell would not comment on the claims because
the company's lawyers have not yet reviewed the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be premature to comment until we get a look at the
lawsuit they're bringing,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford Superior Court Judge Robert Hale threw out similar
claims from the groups last May. Hale found that overfishing -- and
not the power plant -- was responsible for a dramatic decline in
winter flounder in the Niantic Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the groups have prepared a report that tracks the
decline of the winter flounder stock in Long Island Sound to the
point of nearly collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gibson, a fisheries biologist from Rhode Island, reported
that Millstone Unit 3 sucks out about half of the young winter
flounder from the Niantic River.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Utilities' scientists put the loss of young winter
flounder at 12 percent to 18 percent from the Niantic River,
Gibson's report said.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen insist they are not to blame. Medeiros and Maderia
said the area is such poor fishing that the Stonington fleet has
avoided the area for the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   NU said in November it would install a system to prevent larger
fish from being stuck in the water intake screens.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Burton, the lawyer filing the lawsuits, said the system
has not been installed and nothing is being done to prevent the
deaths of juvenile fish.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the environmental groups' claim is scheduled for
May 1 in New London Superior Court. The court has not yet scheduled
a hearing on the fisherman's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal of Hale's decision may be argued before the state
Supreme Court this spring, Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the groups will file an additional lawsuit in
Hartford Superior Court on Monday over state permits for Millstone
Units 2 and 3. Millstone Unit 1 is being decommissioned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-21-00 1606 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
