<HEADLINE> Crisis Spreading to S. Ethiopia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Famine caused by three years of
drought is spreading to areas of southern Ethiopia, the head of the
nation's disaster prevention program said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in the Borena and Omo regions near the Kenyan
border is similar to that in the Somali region in the southeast of
the country, where hundreds are believed to have died and tens of
thousands are arriving at feeding centers in search of food, Simon
Mechale told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Borena and Omo, like the Somali region, are home to semi-nomadic
herders who have lost most of their cattle and goats.
</P>
<P>
   Simon termed the international response to Ethiopia's appeal for
emergency food relief ''not yet enough'' but said interest shown by
international donors is ''encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   The government had appealed for 850,000 metric tons of food for
the 8.1 million drought victims until the end of the year. Simon
said pledges from the United States, the European Union, Canada,
Britain, Italy and France totaled 690,034 metric tons. Only a small
portion has actually arrived in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   Following the devastating famine of 1984-85, a strategic
emergency food reserve was set up here. Because the reserve fund
has been depleted and not replenished, it has reportedly drawn down
to 50,000 metric tons. It is supposed to contain 355,000 metric
tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
