<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Meets Again With Elian's Dad  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Virtually out of options, Attorney General
Janet Reno awaited word Friday from her law enforcement agents in
Miami on the best time for them to remove Elian Gonzalez from his
Florida relatives. But she could not give even his father a
timetable for their reunion.
</P>
<P>
   While Reno clung to hope for a last-minute negotiated turnover,
she held a surprisingly short, 15-minute meeting at the Justice
Department with Juan Miguel Gonzalez, father of the 6-year-old
Cuban boy whom Miami relatives have refused to relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Justice officials said key federal marshals and
immigration agents were being positioned in Miami where Cuban
exiles crowd the street outside the home of Elian's great-uncle,
Lazaro Gonzalez. The boy has stayed there since Thanksgiving when
he was found in the Atlantic after his mother drowned in the
sinking of the ship on which they left Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The exiles, motivated by hatred for Cuban leader Fidel Castro,
have vowed to form a human chain to block Elian's removal. For
days, federal agents have been assessing the crowd's patterns of
activity and consulting with local police.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general ''is looking to our law enforcement
officials to determine the best timing and methods'' for removing
Elian from Lazaro's Miami home, Justice spokeswoman Carole Florman
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Lazaro's house, dozens of exiles prayed; others bore
6-foot wooden crosses representing Jesus' crucifixion on Good
Friday. Most of them said it would be a mistake for the federal
government to try to remove Elian by force.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials, who requested anonymity, said an operation to
retrieve Elian was possible this weekend but was more likely next
week, because of the time required to prepare it and a reluctance
to risk violence over Easter.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Reno, Juan Miguel and his attorney strode
grimly out of the building without comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Reno said she told him ''that I could
not commit to a particular course of action or timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel, who came here from Cuba two weeks ago to pick up
his son, expressed great concern for the boy and appealed to her
for quick action to effect a reunion, Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was deeply moved by Mr. Gonzalez's evident love for his
son,'' Reno said. ''I assured him I would continue working toward
the goal of reuniting him with his child.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, she told reporters, ''I'm exploring every possibility I
can to see this resolved peacefully, promptly and properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she were on the verge of ordering law enforcement
agents to pick up Elian, Reno replied, ''If I were going to do
something like that, I certainly wouldn't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart said the turnover
''should be now done in a prompt and orderly way.'' President
Clinton spoke with Reno about the case for 45 minutes Wednesday
night, but Lockhart labeled as inaccurate news stories suggesting
he was pushing her to use force.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said a ''good volume'' of calls was received on the
White House comment line Thursday night, ''overwhelmingly in favor
of reuniting the boy with his father.'' The Justice Department
received more than 7,000 telephone calls after Juan Miguel Gonzalez
made a televised appeal Thursday afternoon for Americans to urge
Reno and Clinton to act quickly.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, a Republican, urged
Clinton to pursue a mediated agreement in the case. However,
mediation appeared unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Coffey, an attorney for the Miami relatives, said they
have asked the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for supervised
mediation in the case. The court urged both sides Wednesday to
voluntarily submit the four-month-old dispute to its mediation
services, but did not order that.
</P>
<P>
   Justice officials were willing to see a mediator used if both
sides agreed to it for the purpose of discussing how, not whether,
Elian would be transferred to his father's custody. But they said
they had not heard the family drop its demand to debate whether a
transfer should occur.
</P>
<P>
   An option of seeking a federal court order to reinforce Reno's
directive to turn over Elian remained technically alive but had
little support among senior Justice officials, some said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If necessary, the attorney general is prepared to use law
enforcement,'' Justice spokeswoman Florman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have always been three trains moving simultaneously down
the track -- negotiations for a transfer, litigation and law
enforcement,'' Florman said. ''We are no longer in the engineer's
seat on the negotiation train. That's not the train we're
driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Florman said, ''The doors are always going to be
open to the family for a negotiated settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Circuit has ordered Elian to remain in the United
States until the court decides whether he should get an asylum
hearing. A hearing was set for May 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
