<HEADLINE> NYC Firefighters Ignore Call  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- City officials are investigating a fire
company's decision to ignore a call because no one available at the
time had taken a training course to drive the fire engine.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Chief Peter Ganci did not comment on whether any
disciplinary action would be taken against the four firefighters
and one lieutenant from Engine Company 303 in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have five members of the New York City Fire Department with
a fire to respond to, and for whatever reason, contractually or
otherwise, they felt it was not necessary for them to respond,''
Ganci said Friday. ''For me, that was a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred Wednesday when the company's engine
driver, known as a chauffeur, was injured, Ganci said. The
department had asked another driver to substitute, but he did not
arrive by the time of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Ganci said most firefighters have driven the engines, but the
department prefers to use drivers who have undergone specialized
training.
</P>
<P>
   A dispatcher sent a nearby company to handle the blaze, which
was put out with only minor damage done to the building.
</P>
</TEXT>
