<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amato Takes on Public Role in Italy  </HEADLINE>
By VICTOR L. SIMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Giuliano Amato, in line to become the next Italian
premier, first came into the public spotlight as a canny political
risk-taker during the corruption scandals of the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Long a consummate behind-the-scenes operator, Amato, now 61,
became premier during a stormy 10-month period in 1992-1993,
presiding over a coalition rocked by scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Amato's personal probity has never been questioned, however, and
in his post he was able to push through the toughest austerity plan
since the rebuilding years in Italy after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will pack my bags,'' he warned lawmakers at the time, in a
successful move to overcome their reluctance and win passage of $33
billion in spending cuts and $39 billion in new taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ''Dr. Subtle,'' both for his slender frame and
considerable skills, he also devalued the lira during a currency
crisis, then pulled the Italian currency out of the European grid.
</P>
<P>
   Amato did not come under investigation during that stormy era,
when members of his Socialist Party and its allies were dogged by
inquiries begun by Milan's ''Clean Hands'' prosecutors in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Those investigations eventually uncovered a well-oiled system in
which businessmen gave money to politicians or the party in
exchange for deals with the sprawling state economy.
</P>
<P>
   Questions linger about how much Amato knew about kickbacks,
since he headed the office of Socialist premier Bettino Craxi, who
served until 1987 and ever afterwards held considerable influence.
Craxi died in Tunisia last year, refusing to return to Italy to
face corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers said that former anti-corruption prosecutor Antonio
Di Pietro, now a senator, refuses to support Amato.
</P>
<P>
   While Italy does not face the same deep economic or corruption
crisis, Amato will now have to navigate through political perils.
</P>
<P>
   Currently Italy's treasury minister, Amato was the unanimous
choice of a center-left coalition smarting after a humiliating
defeat in regional elections last weekend and trying to stave off a
national election a year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old was the choice of the center-left to succeed
Massimo D'Alema, the first former Communist ever to lead an Italian
government who resigned earlier this week to pay the price for the
election defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Still angry conservative opposition, claiming the center-left
had lost its political legitimacy, demands an immdiate election.
</P>
<P>
   Media mogul Silvio Berlusconi said any candidate taking over
from D'Alema would be no more than a ''useful idiot'' used by the
left to keep the coalition in power.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, now an independent, studied law at the University of Pisa
and received a master's degree in comparative law at Columbia Law
School in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike D'Alema, he speaks fluent English. He has been mentioned
through the years as a candidate for such posts as European Union
president, NATO secretary-general and governor of the European
Central Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1705 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
