<DOCNO> APW20000421.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voters Less Informed With Candidates  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN POPE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Now that Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore have wrapped up their parties' nominations, it
appears voters are forgetting what they had learned about the
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are now less familiar with where candidates stand on
issues than they were two months ago, says a poll released Friday
by the Joan Shorestein Center on the Press, Politics and Public
Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''One might expect citizens to become better informed as the
campaign progresses toward November, but that's not what's
happening,'' said Thomas Patterson, a professor at Harvard's John
F. Kennedy School of Government and co-director of the Vanishing
Voter Project, which conducted the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, voters are forgetting what they learned about the
candidates during the height of the primary season, when coverage
of the races dominated the news.
</P>
<P>
   After February's New Hampshire primary, 24 percent of voters
knew that Bush is opposed to mandatory gun registration. Now that
percentage has fallen to 13 percent. The number of people who knew
Gore opposes vouchers -- or using tax dollars to help parents pay
for their children to attend private or parochial school-- fell from
19 percent to 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The center has surveyed 1,000 adults a week since November to
track familiarity with the candidates' stances on a single issue,
but it started adding more issues in this week's poll. The poll has
an error margin of plus or minus 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, interest in the campaign also declined sharply
once the primary battles were over, the surveys found. The center's
''Voter Involvement Index,'' which measures how closely voters are
following the race in the media and how often they are thinking and
talk about it, peaked on March 12 -- just days after the Super
Tuesday primaries -- then fell this week to its lowest levels since
the first week in January.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said he was surprised by the size of the declines, but
he said the cause is clear: a front-heavy primary schedule that
decided the parties' nominees eight months before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson says voters might know more about the candidates if
the election season were shorter, saying:
</P>
<P>
   ''A shorter, non-interrupted campaign would be from the public's
perspective a more informative campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1723 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Father Urged To Speak For Elian  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cuba's justice minister said Friday that
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez has no right to seek political asylum and
U.S. officials should act quickly to reunite him with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ''A minor of that age does not have the mental, or of course the
legal capacity for a political decision of that nature,'' Roberto
Diaz Sotolongo said in an interview with The Associated Press.
''The son has to speak through the mouth of his father.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta on Wednesday issued
a ruling suggesting that U.S. officials should take the Cuban
child's wishes into account. That was the latest dramatic
development in the legal process that has kept Elian in the United
States since he was rescued from a shipwreck that killed his mother
in late November.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz Sotolongo said the U.S. government has failed to swiftly
enforce its own rulings in the case that Elian belongs with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would have liked that there was much more prompt action...
The declarations of the (U.S.) government have been in accordance
with the law. What has been lacking ... is the quickness in taking
a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister's comments were in line with Cuban government
statements, but far more measured than comments at mass rallies,
where speakers have ridiculed the delay in removing Elian from the
great-uncle in Miami who is fighting to keep the child in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   At a nationally televised rally Thursday, Communist student
leader Hassan Perez labeled great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez a ''vulgar
and common delinquent.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can you explain that the attorney general of that country
is trembling'' to demand the law be carried out, Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta court decision barred Elian from returning to Cuba
until resolution of a legal battle over his Miami relatives'
attempts to seek political asylum for him.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not impede the boy's return to his father's
custody, pending ''whatever other process,'' Diaz Sotolongo noted.
U.S. officials have taken the same position on the court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do in the place of U.S. Attorney General
Janet Reno, who is responsible for carrying out the law and faces a
potentially explosive situation around the Miami house, he
insisted, ''there are sufficient means to ensure compliance.... the
normal ones that are used in such cases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
