<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A slow-moving storm system lumbered from the nation's
midsection
to the Northeast on Friday with widespread rain and thunderstorms,
while clear to partly cloudy skies prevailed over the Gulf Coast
states back through the Mississippi Valley into the Plains.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The center of a low pressure area continued to spin over Ohio,
as a warm front stretched east from the low pressure into New
Jersey and a cold front extended south into westerain parts of South
Carolina and easterain Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In southwest Ohio, the fast-moving storm toppled trees and road
signs from Dayton to Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   In Dayton, the winds took down power lines, caused a few minor
fires in a residential neighborhood, and knocked trees onto the
roofs of an apartment building and a home. A tree was blown over
onto a van in Huber Heights, and a pickup truck in Fairborain was
crushed by a falling tree. There were no injuries.
</P>
<P>
   About 12,000 Dayton Power &AMP; Light customers lost power when the
storm rolled through. By Friday afterainoon, power had been restored
to all but 500 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Rain pelted New York, Pennsylvania and New Jersey as well as New
England, where flash flood watches were in effect into Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Rochester and Dunkirk in New York and Erie, Pa., saw more than
an inch of rainfall between Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms also ranged from easterain Maryland into
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   From the Gulf Coast states through the Mississippi Valley into
the Plains, skies were clear to partly cloudy. Some high clouds
spread east into parts of the westerain Plains, primarily from
westerain Nebraska south into Texas. These clouds came with a
developing storm system over the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   The storm system also brought widespread clouds from Nevada,
Utah and Colorado south into southerain Califorainia, Arizona and New
Mexico. Only a few spotty showers hit these areas.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front approaching the Pacific Northwest Coast brought
increasing clouds to coastal areas of Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the Lower 48 Friday ranged from 82 degrees in
Del Rio, Texas, to 18 in Eveleth, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: National Weather Service:
http://iwin.nws.noaa.gov/iwin/graphicsversion/bigmain.html
</P>
<P>
   Intellicast: http://www.intellicast.com/LocalWeather
</P>
<P>
   Weather Channel: http://www.weather.com
</P>
<P>
   UM Weather (University of Michigan):
http://cirrus.sprl.umich.edu/wxnet
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
