<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Voters Forget About Candidates  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN POPE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Now that Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore have wrapped up their parties' nominations, it
appears voters are forgetting what they had learned about the
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are now less familiar with where candidates stand on
issues than they were two months ago, says a poll released Friday
by the Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and Public
Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''One might expect citizens to become better informed as the
campaign progresses toward November, but that's not what's
happening,'' said Thomas Patterson, a professor at Harvard's John
F. Kennedy School of Government and co-director of the Vanishing
Voter Project, which conducted the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, voters are forgetting what they learned about the
candidates during the height of the primary season, when coverage
of the races dominated the news.
</P>
<P>
   After February's New Hampshire primary, 24 percent of voters
knew that Bush is opposed to mandatory gun registration. Now that
percentage has fallen to 13 percent. The number of people who knew
Gore opposes vouchers -- or using tax dollars to help parents pay
for their children to attend private or parochial school-- fell from
19 percent to 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The center has surveyed 1,000 adults a week since November to
track familiarity with the candidates' stances on a single issue,
but it started adding more issues in this week's poll. The poll has
an error margin of plus or minus 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, interest in the campaign also declined sharply
once the primary battles were over, the surveys found. The center's
''Voter Involvement Index,'' which measures how closely voters are
following the race in the media and how often they are thinking and
talk about it, peaked on March 12 -- just days after the Super
Tuesday primaries -- then fell this week to its lowest levels since
the first week in January.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said he was surprised by the size of the declines, but
he said the cause is clear: a front-heavy primary schedule that
decided the parties' nominees eight months before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson says voters might know more about the candidates if
the election season were shorter, saying:
</P>
<P>
   ''A shorter, non-interrupted campaign would be from the public's
perspective a more informative campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
