<HEADLINE> AM-NY--Church-Window Theft,1st Ld-Writethru,0193  </HEADLINE>
Three stained-glass church windows stolen
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A 20-year-old man has been charged with
stealing three stained-glass window panes worth about $4,500 from a
94-year-old Methodist church.
</P>
<P>
   The man, whose identity was not disclosed, was arrested
Wednesday after police said they got an anonymous tip. By late
Friday, two of the 32-by-13-inch windows had been recovered and
returned to the church.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was charged with fourth-degree grand burglary, a
felony, and others were being sought for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The windows were stolen from the ground level of Grace United
Methodist Church. One was taken the night of April 4 and the others
vanished the next night. Each was valued at around $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ida Miller, the church's pastor for 12 years, was upset
about the theft, but not unforgiving.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was hopeful the church could make contact with the
thief ''and see what can be done to meet this person's need and
maybe be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ''The person is always more important than the window, as
precious as the windows are to us,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
