<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross workers plan to strike  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA TOMMELLEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) -- A threatened strike by nearly 200
American Red Cross workers in Connecticut could drop the daily
collection rate of blood in the state by about 80 percent, the
agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The workers plan to strike May 1 if their demands, which include
improved schedules and benefits, are not met.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not want a strike. This unit does not look forward to
striking and walking a picket line and sacrificing their salaries
and putting their families in jeopardy,'' said Mike Ferrucci Jr.,
executive director of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees, Council 4.
</P>
<P>
   The union currently is negotiating a three-year contract with
the state branch of the American Red Cross Blood Services. The
Connecticut chapter, headquartered in Farmington, runs several
blood donation drives daily around the state. There were a total of
14 scheduled for Friday and Saturday from Danielson to Fairfield.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a strike, the agency plans to hold only one
blood drive a day, reducing its usual daily collection from 600
pints to about 125 pints, said agency spokeswoman Lynn Townshend.
</P>
<P>
   She said the drives will be staffed by management and ''any
union worker who wants to join us.'' Townshend said the state
branch does have as a backup the resources of the National Red
Cross blood collection system.
</P>
<P>
   But during a news conference Friday, union officials said they
don't expect any unionized worker to cross the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   The employees include technician-drivers, nurses, phlebotomists
and lab workers. They say the main sticking point is one more of
respect than wages. They often work long hours, have daily changing
schedules and are asked to pay more of their health benefits. The
pay ranges from $10 to $22 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pelkey, an 11-year worker one of 33 driver-technicians,
said some employees can be at work anywhere from 3 a.m. to 10 p.m.
on any given day to set up blood drives around the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a scheduling nightmare,'' said Pelkey. ''There is no such
thing as a set pattern of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelkey, who also is the president of the union's local unit,
said workers also are looking for some respect. The turnover rate
is about 25 percent, according to the union.
</P>
<P>
   ''We continually work our best to get the blood drives up on
time,'' he said. ''There's never any 'attaboys'. It's always 'you
did something wrong.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He said Connecticut's Red Cross unit is one of the best in the
nation in terms of quantity of blood collected and its safety
record.
</P>
<P>
   ''I take pride in my job because I know I'm helping people in
Connecticut,'' said Pelkey. ''When I started at the Red Cross, I
thought this is the greatest place to be. You were doing such a
humanitarian service.''
</P>
<P>
   The union on Thursday filed a 10-day notice as required by
federal law of their intent to strike. A federal mediator has been
brought in, but no meetings between the two sides had been
scheduled as of Friday, said Jeff Jump, union negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ''The (Red Cross) position is that it's tough on managment to do
the proper scheduling with all the variations. And we're the ones
that bear the brunt of that,'' said Jump. ''It's a heck of a way to
live.''
</P>
<P>
   But the agency contends it has made a fair and generous offer to
the union negotiating team. A strike would not affect Connecticut's
blood supply, but a prolonged strike could ''seriously affect the
region's ability to collect and distribute blood,'' the agency said
in a statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have been negotiating since February. The current
contract expired March 1.
</P>
<P>
   The last strike against the agency was in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public safety is at stake here and management acts like
anyone can do the job,'' said Jump. ''Does John Q. Public want
'just anyone' handling the nation's blood supply?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-21-00 1803 </TRAILER>
