<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auction House Suit Named Class-Action  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge agreed Friday to give class-action
status to lawsuits alleging that Sotheby's and Christie's auction
houses conspired to manipulate prices they were paid by sellers and
buyers for at least seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The number of plaintiffs who have filed lawsuits alleging
antitrust violations ''arguably is alone sufficiently numerous to
justify class-action treatment,'' U.S. District Judge Lewis A.
Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Moreover, the strong likelihood is that the class numbers in
the thousands, if not tens of thousands,'' the Manhattan judge
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's did not oppose the request for class-action status.
Christie's did oppose the request, arguing that class-action status
is inappropriate in what is primarily a damages case.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer and a spokeswoman for Christie's declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Alan Reiss, a lawyer for Sotheby's, said, ''Our view is
that for reasons of efficiencies, it makes a lot of sense to have
this litigated in one court and that's why we didn't oppose it.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is whether there was collusion between the auction
houses that control 95 percent of the $4 billion worldwide auction
market, dominating the U.S. market for auctions of fine and applied
arts, furniture, antiques, automobiles, collectibles and other
items.
</P>
<P>
   In numerous lawsuits, individuals alleged that the auction
houses since Jan. 1, 1993 have agreed to charge buyers the same
rates and since 1995 have agreed to charge the same rates for the
commission sellers must pay.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the auction houses allegedly agreed to stop the
previous practice of negotiating the amounts of sellers'
commissions with some of their customers.
</P>
<P>
   The class certified by Kaplan includes everyone who bought or
sold items from the auction houses between Jan. 1, 1993 and Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The auction houses have said they are cooperating with
prosecutors in a Justice Department investigation that began in
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1822 </TRAILER>
