<HEADLINE> Last World Bank Protesters Released  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The last of the World Bank protesters left
jail Friday night after a plea bargain was reached.
</P>
<P>
   ''The deal was all these charges are papered down to the very
lowest charge on the face of the earth, jaywalking,'' said Mike
Madden, a lawyer representing the demonstrators. He said each would
be fined $5.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 were behind bars at the District of Columbia jail most
of the week after being arrested during protests Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some had claimed they were mistreated in the jail but city
officials denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been no incidents in the jail regarding these
protesters,'' Corrections Director Odie Washington said. He added
that the protesters were kept together in a separate unit of the
jail, away from the regular prison population.
</P>
