<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Hears Good Friday Confessions  </HEADLINE>
By DANIELA PETROFF, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Pope John Paul II led a torch-lit procession around
the ancient Roman Colosseum on Good Friday, leaning on a wooden
cane as he marked Christ's suffering and death on one of
Christianity's most solemn days.
</P>
<P>
   While the pope used to carry a wooden cross for the entire,
half-mile Colosseum procession, after hip surgery a few years ago
he began covering only a stretch of the way with the cross to
commemorate Jesus' suffering on the way to crucifixion. The pope
turns 80 on May 18.
</P>
<P>
   After holding the cross during the first pause for prayer, the
pope, wearing red and white vestments, handed it off in succession
to a Roman family, a Chinese woman, and a young African boy who
lives in a refugee camp in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a grueling Holy Week schedule that included two Masses
on Thursday, as well as confessions of the public and an afternoon
liturgy earlier Friday, John Paul seemed to hold up well during the
Colosseum ceremony, his voice strong and his pace determined. The
event was televised live in many parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The holy week culminates with Easter Sunday Mass in St. Peter's
Square, followed by a papal blessing from the central balcony of
the recently restored basilica, when the Pope will also deliver
Easter greetings in more than 50 languages. Over 100,000 people are
expected to flock to the Easter appearance, one of the highlights
of the Jubilee year celebrating 2000 years since the birth of
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 50,000 pilgrims and tourists, many of them carrying
small torches, converged on the Colosseum, site of some of the
first Christian martydoms at the hands of the Romans, for Friday's
nighttime liturgy.
</P>
<P>
   In brief remarks after the procession, the pope stressed the
contemporary message of the sufferings of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who, if not the crucified son of God, can know the sorrow and
loneliness of so many lives shattered and without a future?'' the
pope said.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul, who is also a poet, playwright and best-selling
author, personally wrote the prayers and meditations that
accompanied the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   It is not ''enough to to wash one's hands,'' the pope said,
referring to the gesture of Pontius Pilate that eventually led to
the crucifixion of Christ. ''Responsibility for the blood of the
just remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in a special ceremony at the Vatican, John Paul
asked for forgiveness for the failings of his church over the
centuries, including its mistreatment of Jews and its violation of
the rights of ethnic groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1852 </TRAILER>
