<HEADLINE> S.Korean Official Quits Before Talks  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A top official of South Korea's ruling
party resigned Friday for allegedly suggesting that Seoul
repatriate convicted North Korean spies, underlying the sensitivity
of relations between the two Koreas ahead of a historic summit.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Lee Jae-jung, chief policy-maker of the
Millennium Democratic Party, came a day before the rivals were to
begin talks at the border village of Panmunjom to discuss the
agenda for the first-ever summit by their leaders in June. The two
Koreas were divided at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published Thursday in Munhwa Ilbo, a South
Korean newspaper, Lee was quoted as saying that Seoul could
consider repatriating convicted North Korean spies as a goodwill
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Ok-du, secretary-general of the ruling party, called Lee's
remarks ''inappropriate,'' saying that the issue is not under
consideration or study by his party or the government.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the two dozen spies were caught during or after the
1950-53 Korean War and are now free after serving prison terms.
However, they remain under protective watch for security reasons
and can't leave South Korea without special government permission.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Lee said their repatriation would be a
conciliatory gesture ahead of the summit and the 50th anniversary
of the outbreak of the Korean War on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, South Korea repatriated one convicted North Korean spy
across the border, hoping that it would lead to improved ties
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   But communist North Korea vehemently charged that the returned
spy became gravely sick because of torture in a South Korean
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions for further repatriations usually invited angry
protests and criticism from conservative groups and media in South
Korea. Lee's statements drew a similar reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ''We suspect that it's part of a secret deal made with North
Korea to hold the summit,'' said Lee Won-chang, spokesman for the
main opposition Grand National Party.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators at Saturday's planned meeting will try to set the
agenda for the June 12-14 summit in the North's capital of
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   They'll begin fashioning a series of topics that could include
missile programs, the U.S. military presence in South Korea, aid
shipments to North Korea, rail links, joint business ventures,
liaison offices and the reunion of separated families.
</P>
<P>
   Both Koreas say reunification is their ultimate goal, but the
sides are expected to avoid focusing on that topic at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Today, two populations that parted at the end of World War II,
and then fought a three-year war, share little more than
bloodlines. The North is poor and totalitarian. The South is rich
and democratic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1920 </TRAILER>
