<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Promotes 'Green' Credentials  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ridiculed as an environmental extremist who
wants to scrap the internal combustion engine, Vice President Al
Gore said on the eve of Earth Day that he wears such criticism as a
''badge of honor.'' Indeed, he said, the auto industry's new
technologies are proving him right.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation celebrates the 31st Earth Day on Saturday, Gore is
focusing anew on the environment, an issue on which his supporters
believe Republican presidential rival George W. Bush is especially
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, however, the Democratic candidate has not been able
to energize environmental activists behind his campaign. Public
opinion polls suggest that while almost everybody wants the
environment protected, people are more interested in such issues as
education, crime and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the vice president flew to the Detroit area, the
heart of America's automobile industry, to highlight the
development of super fuel-efficient engine technology for trucks.
Although not a campaign trip, it was a way for Gore to challenge
the talk of environmental extremism.
</P>
<P>
   He also took after Bush's environmental record, accusing his GOP
rival of ''playing politics with the polluters'' and after five
years as governor leaving Texas ''with the worst environment of any
state.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Texas is No. 1 in the nation for air, water and land
pollution. It's not healthy for people to put up with that,'' Gore
declared in an interview with CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who favors using tax breaks and other incentives to
encourage industry to develop pro-environment programs, said the
current regulatory system that ''dates back to the first Earth
Day'' needs an update.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States is entering a new era of environmental
policy that requires a new philosophy of public stewardship and
personal responsibility,'' Bush said in a statement distributed by
his campaign. ''Economic prosperity and environmental protection
can and must go hand in hand.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 book, ''Earth in the Balance,'' Gore wrote that it
ought to be possible to phase out the internal combustion engine
over 25 years and replace it with a propulsion system that does not
spew out millions of tons of carbon dioxide and other pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's critics have latched on to the proposed demise of the
revered engine, in use since before the days of Henry Ford's Model
T, as proof of extreme environmental thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expected that criticism then and I wear it as a badge of
honor today,'' he declared at a motor freight yard in Romulus,
Mich., outside Detroit, where he announced a new
government-industry research effort aimed at tripling the fuel
economy of trucks. He now sees the development of cleaner, more
efficient engines ''in less than 25 years,'' he said, contending he
had been too conservative when he penned his book eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Few issues distinguish Gore and Bush as clearly as the
environment, according to activists and business executives alike.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has argued for ratification of a climate change treaty that
would require reductions in so-called greenhouse gases, saying it
can be done without jeopardizing economic growth through
development of more efficient automobiles and power plants. Bush
would dump the treaty, crafted in Kyoto, Japan, more than two years
ago, arguing it would devastate businesses and hinder economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   While some environmentalists have criticized Gore for not moving
more aggressively to follow up on the Kyoto agreement, he remains
by far the environmental community's choice over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''The clean air agenda has been largely his agenda,'' said Carl
Pope, executive director of the Sierra Club. ''And he gets credit
in having turned Bill Clinton into a real believer on climate
change. Bush has said he needs to be judged by Texas, and if you
judge him by Texas, the record is appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the Houston area, recorded its first smog violation
of the year, possibly an indicator of a summer of dirty air to
come. Last summer the Houston area, with 52 days of violations, for
the first time passed the Los Angeles basin as having the worst air
quality anywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Texas also spews more toxic chemicals into the environment than
any other state, ranks 49th among all states in state resources for
parks, has been in sporadic fights with the federal government over
endangered species protection and, since Bush became governor, has
seen a spike in the number of dirty air days in eight of its major
metropolitan areas, including Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has blamed the smog problems, in part, on growth and
natural weather patterns and has vowed to work to get urban areas
into compliance with federal air quality requirements.
</P>
<P>
   While Texas emits the most toxic chemicals because of a
concentration of refineries and chemical plants, Dan Bartlett, a
Bush campaign spokesman, said the state also has led the nation in
the reduction of those releases, cutting them by 14 percent between
1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also touts Bush's role in getting industry to make
voluntary cutbacks in air pollution, though environmentalists say
such plans fall short of what's needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1921 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Leader Mentions Reunifying  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's newly elected leader expressed
interest Friday in considering a confederation with rival China -- a
relationship a visiting Chinese policy expert said Beijing would
surely reject.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a list of top Cabinet members in Taiwan's new
government was announced, featuring prominent numbers of women,
technocrats and academics who will be key in the push to improve
relations with China and clean up corruption.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important posts was given to Tsai Ying-wen, an
expert on international trade who will head the Mainland Affairs
Council, which handles China policy.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai, who could be on the front line in possible talks with
Beijing, may have been tapped for her experience in helping to
negotiate Taiwan's bid to join the World Trade Organization. Taiwan
and China are expected to enter the organization that regulates
global trade and will have to negotiate lifting five-decade-old
trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of repairing a 51-year China-Taiwan split by forming a
loose alliance between the two sides, similar to the British
Commonwealth, has been proposed before by Taiwanese thinkers. But
President-elect Chen Shui-bian has not been a vocal proponent of
the notion.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Chen showed flexibility on the issue and said that
creating a confederation might be a way to break the impasse
between China and Taiwan, which separated amid civil war in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The issued was raised by elderly presidential adviser Sun
Yun-suan, whom Chen visited while making traditional courtesy calls
to influential figures in the current government.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said he did not have the power to single-handedly determine
the future of Taiwan and that there would have to be public
consensus before Taiwan pressed ahead in trying to establish a
confederation with the mainland. But he said it was an example of
''new thinking that could bring a breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen added, ''There's a lot of room for discussion of this
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yu Keli, a Chinese scholar with close connections to the
Beijing government, told reporters that China would not agree to
forming a confederation because it wouldn't suit China's current
situation. Yu, who has been visiting Taiwan this week, did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Most polls say that the majority of Taiwanese do not favor
reunification with China as long as it is ruled by a repressive
communist government.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said there was a ''thick icy wall'' between Taiwan and
China, and he warned Beijing that continued threats would only make
relations more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the best way to break down the wall would be to rely
on the warmth of the sun to melt it,'' Chen said, urging Beijing to
use a softer approach.
</P>
<P>
   Since his election last month, Chen has tried to be flexible on
the China issue and has made several goodwill gestures. He has
offered to meet with Chinese leaders and discuss any topic.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has refused to meet with Chen unless he agrees that
Taiwan is an inseparable part of China. Taiwan won't accept the
condition, fearing that as a mere part of China the island wouldn't
be treated as an equal at the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-member Cabinet, picked by Chen and Premier-designate Tang
Fei, includes several members of the Nationalist Party, defeated by
Chen in last month's vote. Tang, the current defense minister, is a
Nationalist.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's small Democratic Progressive Party also won several
appointments. DPP Secretary-general Yu Shyi-kun was named vice
premier and lawmaker Yeh Chu-lan will be transportation minister.
</P>
<P>
   DPP lawmaker Chen Ting-nan will be the justice minister,
responsible for helping Chen keep his promise to clean up graft.
</P>
<P>
   But many other posts were assigned to independents and academics
in keeping with Chen's promise to establish a ''government for all
the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 1940 </TRAILER>
