<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Guerrilla Killed in Attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli forces carried out air attacks in
southern Lebanon on Friday against suspected guerrilla hideouts,
killing a Hezbollah fighter and wounding a 5-year-old boy,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks came as Egypt backed Lebanese claims for Israel to
pay compensations for damage done to Lebanon by hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese President Emile Lahoud and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, meeting in Cairo, also called Israel's decision to
withdraw its 1,500 soldiers from Lebanon by July was ''a victory
for Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   In airstrikes continuing into the night, Israeli helicopter
gunships and planes blasted suspected guerrilla hideouts, killing a
Hezbollah fighter, Lebanese security officials and a Hezbollah
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese officials said an Israeli helicopter gunship fired a
missile that hit the center of Nabatiyeh, a market town 35 miles
south of Beirut. The missile did not explode but caused panic among
the residents.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli military officials denied any attack on the center of
Nabatiyeh.
</P>
<P>
   In a second incident, Israeli artillery shells wounded a boy, 5,
on a farm near Kfar Tibnit, a village about two miles southwest of
Nabatiyeh, Lebanese officials said. The boy was treated for
shrapnel wounds to his legs.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, said in a
statement his forces would ''continue to carry out initiated
actions against the terrorist groups in the air and on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel has occupied a zone in southern Lebanon since 1985 as a
buffer against cross-border guerrilla attacks, but has pledged to
withdrawal by July 7.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting, Mubarak backed Lebanon's claims for Israel to
pay compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lebanon has the right to demand full compensation for the
damage caused by this occupation,'' a joint statement by the
presidents said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Israeli warplanes, retaliating for troop losses,
destroyed three Lebanese power stations. Lebanon said repairs would
cost about $50 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
