<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, April 21, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Gore Questioned on Fund-Raising
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As part of a long-running investigation into alleged
fund-raising abuses in the 1996 Clinton-Gore re-election campaign, federal
prosecutors interviewed President Clinton today. The White House said Vice
President Al Gore also was interviewed by the Justice Department Campaign
Finance Task Force this week. Clinton's interview was conducted under oath and
lasted four hours, said a White House official who spoke on condition of
anonymity. Attorney General Janet Reno established the task force to investigate
allegations that illegal foreign and corporate donations were made in the 1996
presidential campaign.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Intermediaries Help Plan Elian's Transfer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Justice Department spokeswoman said Attorney General
Janet Reno worked with outside intermediaries in Miami today on a possible
agreement that would transfer custody of Elian Gonzalez from his Miami relatives
to his father immediately. Details of the plan have not been worked out, said
Justice spokeswoman Carole Florman. Florman would not identify the
intermediaries other than as members of the Miami community. She said they were
in contact with Elian's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez and his family, who have
defied Reno's order to transfer Elian.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Taiwan's Leader Mentions Reunifying
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's newly elected leader expressed interest
Friday in considering a confederation with rival China -- a relationship a
visiting Chinese policy expert said Beijing would surely reject. On Friday,
President-elect Chen Shui-bian said that creating a confederation might be a way
to break the impasse between China and Taiwan, which separated amid civil war in
1949. Most polls say that the majority of Taiwanese do not favor reunification
with China as long as it is ruled by a repressive communist government.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pilgrims Retrace Jesus' Steps
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Singing hymns and carrying large wooden crosses, throngs of
millennium pilgrims marched in solemn Good Friday processions today, retracing
what tradition says were Jesus' final steps to his crucifixion. The half-mile
Via Dolorosa, or Way of Sorrows, snakes east to west through the walled Old City
of Jerusalem, from the Lion's Gate to the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, where
tradition says Jesus was crucified and buried.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Promotes Environmental Agenda
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ridiculed as an environmental extremist who wants to scrap
the internal combustion engine, Vice President Al Gore said on the eve of Earth
Day that he wears such criticism as a ''badge of honor.'' As the nation
celebrates the 30th Earth Day tomorrow, Gore is focusing anew on the
environment, an issue on which his supporters believe Republican presidential
rival George W. Bush is especially vulnerable. Up to now, however, the
Democratic candidate has not been able to energize environmental activists
behind his campaign.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft Insurer Files Suit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp.'s general insurer has asked a federal court
that it not be required to pay for legal bills stemming from a tide of
third-party antitrust lawsuits filed against the software giant. Both Microsoft
and Zurich American Insurance Inc. confirmed today that they have each filed
suit against the other over the issue. Zurich American, which filed first,
contends Microsoft's liability insurance simply does not cover antitrust issues.
There are nearly 140 private antitrust suits that have been filed in 38 states
against Microsoft, all stemming from the ruling by U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson's rulings that Microsoft acted anticompetitively and broke
antitrust law.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Voters Less Informed With Candidates
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Now that Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore
have wrapped up their parties' nominations, it appears voters are forgetting
what they had learned about the presidential candidates. Voters are now less
familiar with where candidates stand on issues than they were two months ago,
says a poll released today by the Joan Shorestein Center on the Press, Politics
and Public Policy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jordan Mum On Coach Walker's Future
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michael Jordan and Wes Unseld are keeping quiet about the
future of incumbent Washington Wizards coach Darrell Walker. Jordan, the team's
president of basketball operations, and general manager Unseld spent much today
in meetings as they began putting together a blueprint to overhaul the
franchise. While Jordan wants to hire new front-office personnel and trade some
of his high-salary players, one of the top priorities will be hiring a coach.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
