<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Meets With Teamsters President  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) -- On the 61st day, Al Gore ended the news
conference drought. In fact, he held two.
</P>
<P>
   In his first question-and-answer forum with reporters in two
months, the vice president took a few campaign shots at
presidential rival George W. Bush Friday and insisted -- in the
backyard of big-labor China opponents -- that he was making good on
his promise to push for permanent full trade relations with the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also condemned as ''bad business'' a planned meeting --
organized by Michigan Gov. John Engler, an active Bush booster --
that will bring together state regulators and industry groups who
believe federal air-quality standards are too cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Democratic state officials should stay away from
Thursday's gathering, Gore replied, ''I would if the stated purpose
of the meeting is to conspire with the regulated industries on how
to weaken the environmental laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours after he lunched with Teamsters president James Hoffa,
Gore was pressed to prove he was indeed lobbying members of
Congress for the Clinton-Gore administration's plan to give China
permanent normal trade status.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes. Yes I am,'' Gore said, not offering details.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, who continues to withhold a Teamsters endorsement in the
presidential race, hotly opposes the trade measure, and Gore said
he spoke to the labor leader about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to go into my private conversations, but yes I
did and we disagree on it, also,'' Gore told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who was on a part-official, part-campaign
trip to Michigan, spent 20 minutes taking about 20 questions in the
lobby of the Wyndham Garden Hotel, while hotel guests loudly rolled
luggage across the floor nearby.
</P>
<P>
   His second question-and-answer session with reporters came
abroad Air Force Two when he talked about being interviewed by a
Justice Department task force investigating alleged 1996
fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing relaxed, Gore seemed determined not to repeat his
sweaty-browed 1997 press conference after the revelations first
broke and he repeatedly insisted there was ''no controlling legal
authority'' that prevented him from making fund-raising calls from
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''I volunteered to cooperate fully, as I have from the beginning
of their investigation,'' said Gore, who was questioned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether the ongoing investigation might hurt his
presidential campaign, Gore told reporters, ''I have no feelings
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He left the press cabin, but then returned in short order, this
time chewing on a snack and holding a coffee cup. No more
questions. Instead, Gore joked about his press secretary's recent
engagement and signed copies of the re-issue of his 1992 book,
''Earth in the Balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee had been keeping a daily tally
of time elapsed since Feb. 19 when Gore last formally entertained
questions from the crew of reporters who travel with him.
</P>
<P>
   For Friday's occasion, the Gore campaign handed reporters
buttons that said: ''I was at Al Gore's first general-election
press conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore himself laughed off a question about when his next might
be. ''Oh my. It could be any moment.''
</P>
<P>
   He proved himself adept at sticking to his script.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when asked if he had any doubt that Elian
Gonzalez's father genuinely loves his 6-year-old son and wants him
home in Cuba, Gore responded with his usual answer: ''I still think
the standard should be what is in the best interests of the
child.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent the bulk of his seven-hour visit to Michigan on the
chilly loading floor of the Alvan Motor Freight company, where he
beamed pre-Earth Day environmental pitches via satellite to nearly
a dozen TV news stations -- all of them in Midwest swing states.
</P>
<P>
   In the interviews and his news conference, he broke little new
ground, though he did say he has done nothing during the recent
days' developments on the Gonzalez case to press his own views
within the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno is waiting for law enforcement
officials to determine the best time and method to remove the Cuban
boy from the home of his Miami relatives and reunite him with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would recommend a different course to resolve it within the
family,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Political endorsement was not on the day's menu in Romulus,
about 30 miles outside Detroit, Hoffa told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a tough race for everyone. We're not making
any announcement about who we're going to endorse and not
endorse,'' Hoffa said. ''Everything in time.''
</P>
<P>
   His 1.4 million-member Teamsters, the largest of the AFL-CIO's
union affiliates, and the United Auto Workers have held out on
backing Gore, although the AFL-CIO endorsed Gore last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 2010 </TRAILER>
