<DOCNO> APW20000421.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Readies To Change Numbers  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLINE BYRNE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- That British stiff upper lip is trembling in the
face of a crisis of sorts: For the third time in a decade, the
telephone company is changing people's phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Given plenty of advance notice, London restaurants have changed
their menus and matchbooks yet again, and businesses have printed
new stationery and supplies. But the average phone user seems to
have opted for procrastination. Panic set in for some, just hours
before the big changeover of 11.5 million numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Only about four out of every 10 residents affected even know
their new number, said Kevin Read, spokesman for The Big Number,
the phone industry umbrella organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the people in the affected areas are panicking,'' said
Steve Littleton, a supervisor at The Big Number help center in
Bristol. The center is helping field the 150,000 inquiries flooding
in nationally each day.
</P>
<P>
   The change, which went into effect at 1 a.m. local time
Saturday, will alter phone numbers in London, four other British
cities and all of Northern Ireland, with many old numbers rendered
immediately invalid.
</P>
<P>
   Many customers were understandably annoyed when the latest
changes were announced. In 1990, London prefixes had changed from
01 to 071 or 081. Five years later, phone users were told to insert
an 01 in the prefix, thus changing London's to 0171 or 0181.
</P>
<P>
   This time the formula for figuring out the new number is more
complex. Area codes in inner and outer London will change from 0171
and 0181 to 0207 and 0208. Cardiff becomes 029, Coventry 024,
Portsmouth and Southampton 023, and Northern Ireland 028.
</P>
<P>
   New numbers also will be inserted between the new area code and
the old phone number. For example: An old inner London phone number
of 0171-555-5555 becomes 020-7555-5555 and an outer London
0181-555-5555 becomes 020-8555-5555.
</P>
<P>
   ''People just haven't got their head around how to use those
numbers,'' Read said.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the confusion, some old numbers will run in tandem
with the new numbers for varying periods of time. And there's more:
In April 2001, mobile phoners and pager numbers will be changed to
start with 07.
</P>
<P>
   OFTEL, the telecommunication industry's regulatory body, said
the changes are necessary to meet the massive growth in demand for
telephones, fax machines and Internet access. But a scathing report
by the government's Trade and Industry Select Committee last year
offered less than a ringing endorsement of the phone regulator.
</P>
<P>
   ''We find it inexcusable that a cost-benefit analysis was not
used by OFTEL to assess the impact of its current proposals for
changing telephone numbers,'' the committee concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 2019 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Friday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   ----
Teens Try To Deal With Violent High School Attack
</P>
<P>
   ORLEANS, Ontario (AP) -- There will be questions and anguish
about the bloody knife attack at Cairine Wilson high school long
after the bright yellow crime scene tape is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Teens are trying to come to terms with the violent intrusion
into their safe haven Thursday when four students and a lab
technician were attacked with a kitchen steak knife.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries were minor but the incident badly shook the
suburban Ottawa school.
</P>
<P>
   The attack came without warning. There had been no threats of
violence, unlike several schools across Canada bracing for the
first-year anniversary of the school shootings in Columbine, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people are going to be looking over their back a lot
for the next little while at school,'' Kaaveh Shoumanesh, 18, said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The school won't feel as safe until we all get comfortable
again and we also help each other get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   A 15-year-old boy described as a loner who was often teased by
his schoolmates was admitted to hospital with self-inflicted
injuries on his wrists and hands. Police say he will be charged as
soon as today.
</P>
<P>
   ----
Quebec's Duplessis Orphans Press For Apology And Compensation
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Warmed by a new showing of public support,
Duplessis Orphans walked in a cold spring rain Friday to press for
redress for abuse suffered a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   The orphans -- often illegitimate or just children from poor
families -- were warehoused in institutions run by the Roman
Catholic church between 1940 and 1960, during the regime of
iron-fisted premier Maurice Duplessis.
</P>
<P>
   The orphans say many of them were abused. Others were falsely
labeled mentally deficient so the orphanages would get more federal
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors are demanding improved compensation and an apology
for their mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   The group of about 100 walked in silence to denounce the
''conspiracy of silence'' that they say unites the provincial
government, the church, and Quebec's College of Physicians against
them.
</P>
<P>
   But upon reaching their destination at Notre Dame Basilica in
Old Montreal, they were eager to speak out about a public opinion
poll released this week suggesting a majority of Quebecers supports
their demands.
</P>
<P>
   ----
New Wave Of Biker Violence May Be Under Way in Quebec
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- The fatal shooting this week of an elite member
of the Hells Angels appears to have triggered a new wave of
violence in Quebec's biker-gang wars.
</P>
<P>
   With a total of three bikers killed in recent days, expert
investigators say there's no way of knowing how far the attacks,
and the ensuing retaliation, will extend in the gangs' six-year
battle for control of the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   The bloodshed started Monday when Norman Hamel was chased
through a parking lot in suburban Laval and killed by two gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   Hamel, 44, was a member of the Hells Angels' elite Nomad chapter
in Quebec and was said to be close to the gang's reputed head,
Maurice (Mom) Boucher.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, another biker believed to be associated with the
Hells Angels was found dead near a ski center in Piedmont, north of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident was the death Thursday of a 32-year-old man
reported to have connections with a biker gang at odds with the
Hells.
</P>
<P>
   ----
Attorney General Won't Overturn Homolka Plea Bargain
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Despite new public revelations about Karla
Homolka's participation in the sexual torture of young women,
Ontario's attorney general has ruled out overturning her
controversial plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Flaherty says revoking the manslaughter deal that gave the
ex-wife of sex killer Paul Bernardo 12 years is out of the
question, and isn't within his purview.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Flaherty said he is closely watching the
obstruction of justice trial of former Bernardo lawyer Ken Murray.
</P>
<P>
   When it is over, he intends to lobby for changes that will
ensure families are not re-victimized during court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ''The really tragic part is the effect on the families, the
Mahaffy family and the French family,'' Flaherty said, referring to
the relatives of two of Bernardo's teen-age victims.
</P>
<P>
   Murray is on trial in St. Catharines, Ontario, accused of
obstruction after holding on to videotapes depicting the rape and
torture of four Bernardo victims, including Leslie Mahaffy and
Kristen French, for 16 months while he prepared a defense for his
client.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
