<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Fired Over Cheap Gas Prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEWATER, Mass. (AP) -- The operator of a gas station who says
he cut prices out of sympathy for consumers hit by spiraling fuel
costs said Friday he's being fired for selling cheap gas.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Saghbini said the owners of Bridgewater Shell were letting
him go because he recently cut the price of regular gas to $1.39 a
gallon -- 3 cents per gallon less than what he said he paid Shell.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for station owner Motiva Enterprises LLC said
the company made a decision six months ago to close the station
because it had low sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our decision to close the station in 90 days is not associated
in any way with the dealer's current discount program,'' said Shawn
Frederick. ''It was a business decision based upon the fact that
the station is no longer economically viable.''
</P>
<P>
   Saghbini, who has operated the station for more than two years,
dropped the price of regular gas on Monday. Since then, he said,
his business has boomed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have lines all the way to the street,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prices at Massachusetts self-service stations on Friday averaged
$1.54 for regular unleaded gasoline, $1.63 for mid-grade and $1.70
for premium.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm doing it for the consumer,'' Saghbini said. ''The consumer
needs a break.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 2120 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
