<DOCNO> APW20000421.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Bars Adoption Intermediaries  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID McHUGH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia Friday announced it has barred the use of
middlemen in arranging foreign adoptions, a move that complicates
finding new homes for children from the country's often-dismal
orphanages.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective parents will now have to come to Russia and clear
bureaucratic hurdles themselves, a process that can take months,
deputy Education Minister Yelena Chepurnykh told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   However, the new rules will allow foreign adoption agencies to
apply for official registration and open offices in Russia, a move
some U.S. adoption workers have said would be beneficial. The rules
say that accredited agencies could ''offer necessary help in
arranging adoption.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia hasn't started accrediting foreign adoption agencies
under the new rules, and it is not clear how long that will take.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign agencies now use Russian facilitators to help in dealing
with the adoption bureaucracy, allowing adoptive parents to spend
as little as a week in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is the leading source of foreign children adopted in the
United States, with U.S. parents adopting 4,348 Russian kids last
year, according to the U.S. State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has an estimated 600,000 children in some form of state
custody, with little chance of finding adoptive families in their
economically troubled homeland. A 1998 report by the Human Rights
Watch group criticized conditions in orphanages, saying children
were often abused by older children and staff and were frequently
misdiagnosed as mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign adoption has struck a nerve with some communists and
nationalists, who say the process constitutes baby-selling.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules, which were signed by President Vladimir Putin on
March 28, and went into effect Thursday, ban ''intermediaries'' but
allow ''representatives'' without conclusively defining either.
</P>
<P>
   If an adoption is already in progress, it is up to local courts
to decide whether to continue, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 2126 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0166 </DOCNO>
