<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blues 5, Sharks 3  </HEADLINE>
By R.B. FALLSTROM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Chris Pronger snapped a third-period tie with a
power-play goal as the St. Louis Blues staved off elimination with
a 5-3 victory over the San Jose Sharks in their Western Conference
first-round series Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's regular-season champions, who threw away a 3-0
first-period lead before righting themselves, are trying to avoid
becoming the first Presidents' Trophy winner since the 1991 Chicago
Blackhawks to get eliminated in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks carry a 3-2 series lead into Sunday's Game 6 in San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues' big three, under fire for lack of production or
undisciplined play on Pronger's part, all made contributions. Al
MacInnis scored his first goal of the playoffs and had an assist,
Pierre Turgeon had two assists, and Pronger kept his cool, spending
only two minutes in the penalty box after totaling 24 the first
four games.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis also trailed 3-1 in the first round last year against
the Phoenix Coyotes, and prevailed in seven games. Fifteen teams
have surmounted a 3-1 series deficit in NHL history, including the
Blues on three occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ricci had a goal and an assist and Vincent Damphousse had
two assists for the Sharks, who are trying for their third
first-round upset in seven seasons. Ricci and Brad Stuart scored on
the power play for San Jose, which has five man-advantage goals in
the series.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger got his second goal of the playoffs at 3:54 of the
third, tapping the puck into the net after a cross-ice feed from
Jochen Hecht. The goal came with Stephane Matteau off for boarding
after running Lubos Bartecko headfirst into the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Young added an empty-net goal with 33.9 seconds left, off
another feed from Hecht.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues came out flying, with three good scoring chances
stopped by Steve Shields before Ladislav Nagy, a 20-year-old
rookie, scored on the rebound of a Dave Ellett drive at 4:04.
Thirty seconds later, and only five seconds after Marco Sturm was
whistled for high-sticking, MacInnis got his first goal of the
playoffs on a slap shot at 4:39.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:13, Ricard Persson slipped the puck through a maze of
skates from the side of the net to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues took the game's first 10 shots, and Roman Turek didn't
even handle the puck until the 10:30 mark. The Sharks got their
first shot, by Damphousse from the right circle on a power play, at
13:16 of the first.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose took advantage of Blues penalties later in the period
to rally, narrowing the shots gap to 11-7 at the end of the period.
Ricci scored his third goal of the playoffs on a backhander from in
front of the net on a power play at 18:52.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks carried the play in the second period, after which
the Blues' shots advantage was whittled to 20-19, and tied it on a
backhander by Jeff Friesen at 12:26 and a drive from the point by
Brad Stuart at 17:03. Friesen's goal deflected off the skate of
Blues defenseman Jeff Finley, continuing a trend of fortuitous
bounces for the Sharks, for his first point of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Turek was screened on Stuart's goal, which came on a power play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 2217 </TRAILER>
