<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blazers-Timberwolves To Face Off  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- When a reporter dared to suggest that the
Minnesota Timberwolves had an even chance against the Portland
Trail Blazers because the teams split their four regular-season
games, Scottie Pippen questioned the basic laws of arithmetic.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's evenly matched about that?'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the best-of-five series that begins Sunday, the
numbers don't quite add up for the Timberwolves. They are 0-3 in
the playoffs since the franchise began playing in 1989, while the
Blazers have made the postseason 18 straight years and 23 of the
last 24.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota did finish with a franchise-record 50 victories,
including two in its last two games against the Blazers. But
Portland blew second-half leads in both games, and the Timberwolves
needed shots in the final seconds to win. Kevin Garnett banked in a
10-foot jumper with 3.3 seconds left to win 98-96 on Jan. 6 in
Minneapolis, and Joe Smith got a 17-footer to fall in off the glass
with 15.1 seconds left for a 96-92 victory March 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not to take anything away from them, but we kind of beat
ourselves,'' reserve center Jermaine O'Neal said. ''We're very
deep, and we have a ton of talent. I don't think they have enough
firepower to compete with our rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   The marquee individual matchup will be Garnett against Rasheed
Wallace, two of the most emotional and exciting power forwards in
the league. Like their teams, the players battled to a dead heat on
paper this season. Wallace averaged 20 points in the four games,
Garnett 20.3. Wallace outshot Garnett 63 percent to 44, but he was
outrebounded 45-19 and played 21 fewer minutes in the two losses
because of fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can get him outplaying Kevin and matching up with him
real well and not get in foul trouble, it should be over in
three,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Wallace can handle Garnett virtually by himself, the
Blazers should have a huge advantage inside. Portland center
Arvydas Sabonis, who missed the Jan. 6 game with an upper
respiratory infection and was out nine games late in the season
with a sprained right foot, averaged 10.3 points and 9.3 rebounds
in his three games against Minnesota, compared with 6.0 points and
6.3 rebounds on 27 percent shooting for Timberwolves centers
Radoslav Nesterovic and Dean Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and Garnett ''are both going to get 20 a night, so it's
a wash,'' Blazers point guard Damon Stoudamire said. ''So it's
going to come down to everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland led the NBA in field-goal shooting at 47.0 percent,
just ahead of No. 2 Minnesota at 46.7. The Timberwolves are a
better shooting team, with point guard Terrell Brandon driving and
feeding Garnett and Smith or hitting mid-range jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We definitely don't want to get into a jump shooting
contest,'' Brian Grant said. ''If we're contesting every shot and
we've got a hand in their face and they're hitting them, then
there's nothing we can do about that. Except for when the ball does
come off, we make sure we limit them to one shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon has gotten the best of fellow Portland high school star
Damon Stoudamire, outscoring his close friend 84-48 and getting 10
more assists and six fewer turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a nice battle, but I'm not here to talk about
me and Terrell,'' Stoudamire said. ''When he tends to play well,
they tend to play well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
