<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From Friday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Yankees-Blue Jays:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK YANKEES: Andy Pettitte reported no problems after
throwing off a mound for the first time since being placed on the
disabled list with a strained left lateral muscle. The left-hander
threw 50 pitches. He'll throw off the mound again on Sunday, and is
expected to start on Tuesday. ... Roger Clemens, who left
Wednesday's game against Texas with a stiff back, said he'll try to
see a chiropractor in Toronto this weekend. He's expected to make
his next start. ... Yankees' manager Joe Torre said Scott Brosius
may return to the lineup as soon as Tuesday. Brosius is on the
disabled list with a strained rib cage.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: OF Shannon Stewart missed his seventh straight game
with a pulled quadriceps and strained right hamstring. ... Last
year, the Blue Jays were 2-10 vs. the Yankees. ... Right-hander
Joey Hamilton faced live hitters for the first time in more than a
month on Friday. Hamilton, on the DL since March 21, threw 12
minutes of BP at Grant Field in Dunedin, Fl. ''I threw all
fastballs, four seamers, cutters'', said Hamilton, ''My arm felt
good and it was a very positive outing. I look forward to pitching
BP again in five days, maybe four.'' Hamilton will throw again on
April 25 or 26 against extended spring hitters.
Angels-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Bench coach Joe Maddon went to St. Anthony's Hospital
in St. Petersburg after feeling ill for two days. Tests were
negative and he returned to Tropicana Field for the game. ...
Manager Mike Scioscia expects SS Gary DiSarcina (bruised thumb) to
be ready to come off the disabled list on Monday. ... Friday night
began a stretch in which the Angels will play seven of 10 games
against the Devil Rays. ... RHP Tim Belcher, recovering from elbow
surgery, allowed one baserunner in five innings of a start for
Class A Lake Elsnore on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Manager Larry Rothschild juggled the batting order
with Greg Vaughn moving from fifth to third, Jose Canseco dropping
from third to cleanup, and Fred McGriff from fourth to fifth. ''It
doesn't change things a whole lot. We've hit fairly well, but we
haven't produced runs and that's the name of the game,'' Rothschild
said. ... LHP Wilson Alvarez, on the DL with a sore pitching
shoulder, played catch before the game and continued to feel
stiffness.
Twins-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: OF Torii Hunter wasn't in the Minnesota starting
lineup for the first time this season. Hunter, a .294 hitter who
has hit safely in 12 of 17 starts this season, was just getting a
break. The Twins opened a six-game road trip, three games at Texas
before three at the New York Yankees. ... The current Twins roster
includes four rookies -- pitchers Mark Redman and Johan Santana,
catcher Matt LeCroy and infielder Jason Maxwell. They are among 12
players who weren't with Minnesota at the start of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: After not starting the Rangers' last game, SS Royce
Clayton was back in the lineup Friday -- batting ninth instead of in
the leadoff spot like he did the first 14 games. Clayton, who never
made the transition to the leadoff spot in St. Louis, hit just .164
at the top of the Texas lineup. Manager Johnny Oates believes that
moving Clayton from the top spot will help him get on track. ''I'd
like to try something different for a day or two to see how things
work. I will move him back when he gets started,'' Oates said. ...
LHP Justin Thompson, who started the season on the disabled list
while still recovering for shoulder surgery last August, started
for Double-A Tulsa on a medical rehab assignment Thursday and
reported no physical problems. He threw 90 pitches over 5 2-3
innings, allowing three earned runs on eight hits. He struck out
four and walked one. His next scheduled start is Tuesday for
Triple-A Oklahoma.
Tigers-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Tigers OF-DH Juan Gonzalez disputed a report on ESPN's
Web site that he'd told opponents he had no intention of signing a
long-term deal with the Tigers. Gonzalez said he hadn't made up his
mind on his future: ''I can either play here one year, I don't
know, stay here, I don't know, or go to free agency, I don't know.
Right now I'm here for play baseball,'' he said. ... Manager Phil
Garner, his team shut out four times in the first 14 games, said:
''We are not as bad as we are right now.'' Detroit was blanked 12
times all last season. Garner said the defense has also been
disappointing. ''We haven't made plays to get us out of jams,'' he
said. ...The Tigers were 11-for-57 (.193) with runners in scoring
position during their recent eight-game homestand. Detroit was tied
with Oakland last season for the majors' worst average (.243) with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO WHITE SOX: RHP James Baldwin, who missed his last start
after being hit in the chest by a line drive, is scheduled to pitch
again Sunday against the Tigers. Baldwin suffered a bruised rib.
... LHP Mike Sirotka, who missed his previous start with a tender
forearm, played toss Friday and said his arm felt better. He's
scheduled to pitch Tuesday against Baltimore. ... The White Sox
claimed 3B Herbert Perry off waivers from Tampa Bay and plan to
have him for Sunday's series finale against the Tigers. Perry would
be the fourth player to play third base this season, joining Craig
Wilson, Greg Norton and Paul Konerko.
Royals-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: RHP Jay Witasick, who is 0-3 with a 10.13 ERA this
season, will start Saturday after missing his last turn because of
arm fatigue and soreness in his right biceps. In his last start,
Witasick went 3 2-3 innings in a 7-5 loss to the New York Yankees.
He allowed five runs and seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: LHP Jamie Moyer was placed on the 15-day DL because of
a strained muscle in the back of his left shoulder. The move is
effective to April 15. He is expected to be out about three weeks.
RHP Brett Tomko was recalled from Triple-A Tacoma to take Moyer's
starting spot on Saturday. Tomko, who was acquired in the Feb. 10
trade for Ken Griffey Jr. with Cincinnati, was bothered by soreness
in his left Achilles' tendon all spring.
Athletics-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND-- Shortstop Miguel Tejada signed an $11 million,
four-year deal Friday. He's batting .268 with a homer and nine
RBIs. ... Oakland DH John Jaha is having a tough time making
contact. He has 16 strikeouts in his 28 at bats, including five in
Thursday night's game at Cleveland. He is the fourth Oakland player
to fan five times in a game. The others were Reggie Jackson, Rick
Monday and Jose Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE-- Baltimore right-hander Scott Erickson, who underwent
surgery in early March to remove bone chips from his right elbow,
is being sent out on a rehab assignment. He is scheduled to report
to Single A Frederick on Tuesday in his first outing since
undergoing the arthroscopic surgery. ... The 7-8-9 spots in the
Orioles batting order have combined to hit .333 (49-147) with 10
home runs, 37 runs scored and 40 RBIs.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Brewers-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Neither SS Mark Loretta nor OF James Mouton started
Friday night for the Brewers, though both were available off the
bench. Loretta left Thursday night's 5-4 loss in New York with a
mild concussion in the sixth inning after he collided with Mouton
while fielding a pop foul. ... The Brewers entered Friday's game
with a combined record of 81-65 in Canada, having gone 75-62 in
Toronto and 6-3 in Montreal. Milwaukee is 164-121 overall against
the two Canadian teams. ... The Brewers were trying to avoid losing
five straight for the first time since last Aug. 20-24.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: With three off days scheduled through May 4, the Expos
plan to go with a four-man rotation of Dustin Hermanson, Hideki
Irabu, Javier Vazquez and Carl Pavano. Jeremy Powell, who started
but did not figure in the decision in Thursday night's 10-6 loss to
Chicago, was optioned to Triple-A Ottawa following the game. INF
Andy Tracy contract was purchased from Ottawa, he will be used as a
left-handed bat off the bench. ... Closer Ugueth Urbina's next save
will be his 106th, moving him one ahead of John Wetteland for the
third highest total in franchise history. Mel Rojas is second with
109, while Jeff Reardon is the Expos' career leader with 152 from
1981-86.
Phillies-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: The Marlins still have high hopes for Ramon Castro,
acquired last July from Houston and penciled in during the
offseason as the team's starting catcher. After a disappointing
spring, Castro was sent to Triple-A Calgary, where he was hitting
.294 through Wednesday. ''We do envision that Ramon Castro will be
our No. 1 one, everyday catcher,'' Florida general manager Dave
Dombrowski said. ''We're going to let him keep going, watch him
play, and make those decisions.'' ... It is quite possible that the
Marlins will not finish the season playing their home games at Pro
Player Stadium. If so, the reason won't be the construction of the
new ballpark they want. Rather, it will be due to the fact that a
bankruptcy judge has given permission to stadium officials to seek
another naming-rights partner. Fruit of the Loom, the company that
four years ago signed the $20 million, 10 year contract for the
naming rights, filed for bankruptcy in December and closed its Pro
Player sports clothing division about two months ago. ''We're
moving right along very quickly now that in the last few days we
got the ability to find a new naming-rights partner,'' said stadium
president Bruce Schulze, who indicated that his goal was to have a
new deal in place by the start of the football season.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Curt Schilling made his fourth rehab start
Thursday night for Philadelphia's A Clearwater affiliate. Facing
St. Petersburg, Schilling pitched eight innings, allowing one run
and four hits, while striking out four. He threw 91 pitches, 60 for
strikes. Schilling will next see action when he starts Tuesday for
Triple-A Scranton/Wilkes-Barre against Ottawa. If all goes well, he
will make his Phillies debut on April 30 in Philadelphia against
St. Louis. ... Paul Byrd, Philadelphia's scheduled starter for
Saturday's second game of the series against the Marlins, has a
1.01 career ERA in seven appearances at Pro Player Stadium, his
lowest ERA at any ballpark. He has given up just three earned runs
in 26 2-3 innings pitched.
Dodgers-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: Gary Sheffield singled in the first inning against
Cincinnati on Friday night. He has reached base in each of his 15
games. ... Heading into the game, Sheffield had a .190 career
average in Cincinnati, his lowest in any NL park.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: The helmet that Ken Griffey Jr. wore when he hit his
400th homer in Colorado is heading to baseball's Hall of Fame.
Griffey was the youngest to reach the 400-homer mark, and the Hall
asked for a memento to put on display. Griffey signed the helmet
and added the date of the homer -- April 10 -- before it was shipped
off. ... Reliever Mark Wohlers threw 35 pitches Friday, two days
after an encouraging batting practice session in which he threw the
ball hard and straight. Wohlers, 30, had reconstructive elbow
surgery last July 6 and is four weeks ahead of schedule in his
comeback. He hopes to be able to rejoin the team in June.
Pirates-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: RHP Brad Clontz, who began his major league career
with the Braves, was recalled by the Pirates. He went to spring
training with Arizona, was released and signed by Pittsburgh and
sent to their Nashville Triple-A club where he allowed no runs in 4
2-3 innings of relief. ... RHP Jose Parra made his first appearance
Friday in the majors since Sept. 29, 1996 with the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: LHP Bruce Chen was recalled from Triple-A Richmond
after RHP Kevin McGlinchy went on the DL. Chen started the season
with Atlanta and pitched four innings, allowing one run. He pitched
six scoreless innings Tuesday for Richmond. ... Andres Galarraga,
who hit two home runs in Atlanta's 10-1 win Thursday, has 338 in
his career, tied for 64th with Cubs manager Don Baylor.
Padres-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Catcher Wiki Gonzalez's 10-game hitting streak is the
longest of his career. He has hit .394 (13-for-33) during it. ...
Coming into new Enron Field, the Padres were 6-3 playing in new
stadiums. That includes wins at Cincinnati's Riverfront,
Philadelphia's Veterans, Montreal's Olympic, Florida's Joe Robbie,
Colorado's Mile High and Seattle's Safeco Field and losses at
Pittsburgh's Three Rivers, Colorado's Coors Field and Atlanta's
Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: The MRI on Moises Alou's strained calf showed no
serious damage Wednesday but club officials said they didn't expect
him to play in the next two or three days. Alou has missed the last
four games with the injury. ''We're optimistic that he'll be ready
to play by Tuesday,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. Manager
Larry Dierker said he might use Alou as a pinch-hitter this
weekend. ... Dierker admits he's worried about the Astros' 6-8
start. ''It's not something that we feel desperate about yet,'' he
said. ''When you have slump during the season, you don't notice it
as much because you've played well and you know you will again. But
now, we've got to play well just to prove to ourselves we can.''
Rockies-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Brian Bohanon, who lost his spot as a starter after
posting a 15.68 ERA in three starts may move back into the rotation
to replace Rolando Arrojo who was injured Thursday while covering
home plate. Arrojo was placed on the disabled list with a popped
hamstring. His place on the roster was filled by pitcher Kevin
Jarvis who was called up from Triple-A Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: The Cardinals are looking for a closer to backup Dave
Veres. Manager Tony La Russa said Healthcliff Slocumb, with 97
career saves, is the most likely candidate for the role on nights
when Veres is not available. Slocumb has been used as a setup man
since the Cardinals acquired him last year. ... Alan Benes, trying
for a comeback after two shoulder operations, threw 72 pitches
while allowing one run in 3 2-3 innings Thursday night at Triple-A
Memphis.
Giants-Diamondbacks:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: The Giants 4-11 start going into Friday night's
game is their worst since 1983. The Giants haven't started 4-12
since 1951, the year they came back from 13{ games behind in August
to win the pennant on Bobby Thomson's ''shot heard 'round the
world.'' ... Entering Friday's game, the Giants were 1-7 in
contests decided by two runs or less and 0-5 against NL West foes.
... San Francisco is in the midst of an eight-game road trip that
will take the team 8,211 miles to Cincinnati, Phoenix and Florida,
then back home.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: The Diamondbacks designated right-handed reliever
Darren Holmes for assignment to make room for closer Matt Mantei,
who was activated from the disabled list. Holmes declined an
assignment to Triple-A Tucson, and will be released if he isn't
traded in the next 10 days. ... Tony Womack, who flew to Virginia
for the funeral of his grandmother on Monday, will miss Sunday's
series finale to fly to New York for the funeral of his
father-in-law. ... Diamondbacks pitchers lead the majors with a
3.10 ERA. Randy Johnson leads the way with a 0.76 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
