<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Arrives in Greece  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin discussed
cooperation in trade and tourism on the first day of his visit to
Athens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's trip to Greece, following visits to the Middle East and
Turkey, comes as China tries to raise its international profile and
play a more active role as a permanent member of the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   China is also seeking to improve ties with the European Union,
of which Greece is a member, Zhu Bangzao, the Chinese foreign
ministry spokesman, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Current cooperation in economics and technology is good, and
trade between them is growing strongly, said Zhu. China also signed
an agreement with Greece to import a total of 200,000 tons of
aluminum, with the first 40,000 tons, valued at $9 million, being
shipped this year, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, the first Chinese president to visit Greece, was
reciprocating for a trip to China by Greek President Costis
Stephanopolous.
</P>
<P>
   Greece and China have enjoyed warm ties in recent years, boosted
by Chinese support for the failed Greek bid to gain a non-permanent
seat on the United Nations Security Council in 1998, Greek foreign
ministry officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang also spoke of boosting the tourist trade, saying China is
gradually beginning to allow some of its citizens to travel beyond
its borders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 2237 </TRAILER>
