<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Concern Grows in Little Havana  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN FARRINGTON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Demonstrators gathered in prayer outside the Miami
home of Elian Gonzalez on Good Friday, saying the U.S. government
should not try to force a reunion between the boy and his Cuban
father during the Easter holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Religious icons, flowers and photos of the 6-year-old Cuban boy
were in makeshift shrines throughout heavily Catholic Little
Havana.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor set up a life-sized statue of St. Lazarus, one of
Cuba's most revered religious symbols. The statue, draped in a
purple cape and propped up by crutches, has photo of Elian at its
feet, next to a printout saying ''God can make the impossible
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the home of Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, a painting
of another Cuban saint, the Virgen of Charity of Cobre, hung on the
front door. Cubans say she appears to rafters on their way to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of exiles prayed; others bore 6-foot wooden crosses
representing Jesus' crucifixion on Good Friday. Rosaries and other
religious items decorated the chain-link fence in front of the
house.
</P>
<P>
   Only two days after protesters celebrated a court ruling keeping
Elian in the country for now, some said there was growing concern
that he will soon be taken away by force. The crowd grew to about
600 Friday evening, causing rising tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We won a small victory, but we have the worry that immigration
is going to get Elian soon,'' said Ana Silverio, 48, referring to
the Immigration and Naturalization Service. ''We're praying so that
whatever God decides is what happens. I hope they respect these
holy days and they don't come in until after.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Attorney General Janet Reno met at the Justice
Department with the boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, but
declined to provide him with a timetable of what may happen.
</P>
<P>
   The developments in Washington caused rising tension here.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's beginning to build up again unfortunately,'' said Ramon
Saul Sanchez, the president of the anti-Castro Democracy Movement
who urged demonstrators to remain peaceful. ''The sense is that
maybe Monday or Tuesday, but the people are still worried, because
you never know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
