<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers 9, Reds 2  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Barry Larkin tore a finger ligament and went
into surgery, Ken Griffey Jr. hurt his back and Cincinnati's
pitching staff stumbled again, completing an all-around miserable
night for the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley homered and Kevin Elster hit a ninth-inning grand
slam off Norm Charlton on Friday night as the Los Angeles Dodgers
took advantage of the Reds' mounting woes for a 9-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin, the Reds' shortstop and captain, tore a ligament in the
middle finger of his glove hand while diving for Mark
Grudzielanek's two-run single in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin's glove caught on the artificial turf as he dove,
twisting his hand. He immediately went to a hospital for surgery
and will be out for two-to-four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   His injury came two days after first baseman Sean Casey returned
from a broken right thumb sustained in the final exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   There was more. Griffey hurt his back, evidently while diving
for a ball in centerfield in the second inning, and frequently bent
over to stretch during the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey was 1-for-3 with a double and a pair of walks and could
only jog out a fourth-inning grounder, but played the entire game.
A trainer came out to talk with him after one painful swing in the
second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers overcame a ragged start by Eric Gagne to win a game
that will be remembered more for the subplots. It started 27
minutes late because clubhouse attendants had to go on a
last-minute shopping spree when the umpires' equipment got
misdirected to New York.
</P>
<P>
   With the crew wearing black golfers' rain suits on a damp and
raw night, both starting pitchers struggled with their control and
the cold, frequently blowing on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Herges (1-0) got his first major league win by pitching 2
2-3 hitless innings in relief of Gagne, who threw 117 pitches in 4
1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Elster topped it off with a ninth-inning slam off Charlton, who
walked the bases loaded before giving up the first-pitch homer in
his first appearance for the Reds since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Parris (1-3) had a bases-loaded double in the second for
both of Cincinnati's runs, but lasted only two-plus innings. The
right-hander gave up seven hits and two walks, needing 46 pitches
to get through the second inning alone, as his ERA climbed to 8.47.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, only 2-for-14 on the Dodgers' recent homestand, led off
the second with his third homer. Grudzielanek's single up the
middle that eluded Larkin made it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Parris' first double since 1995 cut it to 3-2 in the bottom of
the inning as Gagne struggled almost as much. The right-hander
threw 43 pitches in his half-inning.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles made it 5-2 in the third when Adrian Beltre got a
two-run single on a ball that deflected off the glove of reliever
Scott Sullivan and rolled through the hole at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Gagne had an embarrassing moment in the seventh, when he
came to bat and went to first base on what he mistakenly thought
was ball four. He was summoned back to home and struck out on the
next pitch. ... Gagne struck out eight, matching his career high.
... Kevin Elster hit his third career grand slam, first since 1996.
... Larkin singled in the first inning and got the 350th stolen
base of his career. ... The helmet that Griffey wore when he hit
his 400th homer in Colorado is heading to baseball's Hall of Fame.
... The Reds threw two more wild pitches, giving them 17 in 17
games -- most in the majors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-21-00 2306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000421.0196 </DOCNO>
