<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Team Wins Marbles Tournament  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TINSLEY GREEN, England (AP) -- An American dream team captured
the International Cup in a marbles tournament Friday, defeating the
English champs at a village pub.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was America's first in the contest since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really shot some unbelievable marbles,'' coach Jeff Kimmell
said after the eight-hour event. ''We're getting ready to go
celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were undefeated through six games, said Sam
McCarthy-Fox, secretary of the British Marble Board of Control,
which organizes the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmell, 32, a computer network engineer and former national
marbles champion from Middletown, Md., hand-picked and rigorously
trained the team of 10, most of them teen-agers, from Maryland,
Pennsylvania and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Winners receive no cash, but Kimmell hopes his team's success
will bolster his quest to have team marbles made a demonstration
sport in the 2004 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. players included six former winners of the U.S.
National Marbles Tournament held each June in Wildwood, N.J. They
ranged in age from 15 to 35 and hailed from Maryland, Pennsylvania
and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The annual tournament held outside The Greyhound pub in Tinsley
Green, West Sussex, drew a crowd of about 500 to watch the best of
players at an ancient game that is believed to have come to Britain
with the invading Romans a couple of thousand years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
