<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruiz Wins 3-Meter Diving Title  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Mark Ruiz, the two-time U.S. diver of the
year, won the 3-meter springboard title Friday in the U.S. National
Indoor Diving Championships for his 14th national title.
</P>
<P>
   The Puerto Rico native received two 8.5s and two 8.0s on his
final dive -- a reverse 3{ summersault with a one-half twist tuck --
to edge David Pichler.
</P>
<P>
   ''I looked at the scoreboard and I was at 650,'' Ruiz said.
''Then I looked at David's score (649.26), because I wasn't totally
sure if I had won. Once I checked out the scores, I was all
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Going into the last two dives, I still knew I had a good
chance. I saw the scores, and I knew exactly what I needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz was the star of the championships a year ago, becoming the
first to sweep all three men's springboard titles since Olympic
gold medalist Greg Louganis in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But this week has been rough for Ruiz. A nagging groin injury
was compounded by fatigue when Ruiz flew to Minneapolis last
Saturday, less than a day after escorting his girlfriend to her
senior prom in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been tired, and I pulled the groin again on my third
dive,'' he said. ''But I really wanted to win this week. It was a
good last dive, you can't get any better than that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Reiling, of Roseville, Minn., was the surprise winner in
the 4-meter competition. Reiling's fourth dive, a reverse 2{
summersault, earned two scores of 9.5 and four at 9.0.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew it was a fairly good dive, but I came up and I did not
believe my score,'' she said. ''I was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiling finished with 499.83 points, with Ashley Culpepper, of
Baton Rouge, La., second at 493.14.
</P>
<P>
   Lauryn McCalley and Lane Bassham won the women's synchronized
3-meter championship. They combined to score 286.20 points,
finishing ahead of Kathy Pesek and Tracy Bonner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
